ited Kingdom for English constituencies|Denison-Pender, John]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918|Denison-Pender, John]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1918\u20131922|Denison-Pender, John]]\n[[Category:Members of London County Council|Denison-Pender, John]]\n[[Category:British people of Cornish descent]]\n[[Category:British Army General List officers]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1929-1945 \u2192 1929\u20131945 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Denison-Pender,_1st_Baron_Pender"}
{"title_page": "James Dawes (British politician)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n[[File:James Arthur Dawes.jpg|thumb|right|James Arthur Dawes]]\n'''James Arthur Dawes''' (16 June 1866 \u2013 14 November 1921) was an English [[solicitor]], businessman and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) from 1910 to 1921.\n\n== Family and education ==\nJames Arthur Dawes was the son of Richard Dawes of Castle Hill, [[Ealing]], [[Middlesex]], a solicitor in Angel Court, [[Throgmorton Street]], London. He was educated at [[Harrow School]] and [[University College, Oxford]] where he gained [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|MA]] and [[Bachelor of Civil Law]] degrees. In 1920 he married Violet Pridmore from [[Penge]] in [[Surrey]].<ref name=\"Who was Who, OUP 2007\">''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref> They do not appear to have had children.\n\n== Career ==\nDawes qualified as a solicitor in 1891 <ref>The Times, 31 January 1891 p13 & 21 November 1891 p10</ref> and was admitted to his father's firm, Mssrs. Dawes and Sons, in January 1892 <ref>The Times, 8 January 1892 p9</ref> He was later a [[Justice of the Peace]] for the [[County of London]].<ref name=\"Who was Who, OUP 2007\" /> From the outset of the First World War, Dawes served with the [[Royal Naval Reserve]] and [[Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve]] raising to the rank of acting [[Commander (Royal Navy)|Commander]] by 1918.<ref name=\"Who was Who, OUP 2007\" /> He was engaged in mine-sweeping operations and from July 1918 he served at the [[Admiralty]].<ref>The Times, 12 December 1918 p9</ref> Unsurprisingly, one of Dawes recreations was [[yachting]].<ref name=\"Who was Who, OUP 2007\" />\n\n== Southwark and London Politics ==\nDawes had a home in [[Kennington Park Road]] in [[Southwark]]. He took a strong interest in local affairs <ref>''The Times House of Commons 1910'', Politico\u2019s Publishing 2004 p26</ref> and was Chairman of the Vestry of Newington, the equivalent of a [[Parish councils in England|Parish council]], from 1897\u20131900. Dawes was then the first [[Mayor]] of the [[Metropolitan Borough of Southwark|Borough of Southwark]] from 1900\u20131901 and Deputy Mayor the following year.<ref>The Times, 5 September 1902 p11</ref> He was re-elected Mayor in 1913\u201314 <ref>The Times, 11 November 1913 p4</ref> and 1914\u201315. He also served as a founder member of the [[Metropolitan Water Board (London)|Metropolitan Water Board]] in 1903\u20131904. He was later elected as a member of the [[London County Council]] for the [[Progressive Party (London)|Progressive Party]] for  Newington Walworth for various years between 1906 and 1913.<ref>The Times, 4 March 1907 p6; 7 March 19109, p7; 7 March 1913, p9</ref> In 1911 Dawes was appointed to the Joint Committee of the two Houses of Parliament to consider the Bill promoted by the Metropolitan Water Board to construct a series of new works and reservoirs on the [[River Thames]] at [[Staines]].<ref>The Times, 31 March 1911 p4</ref>  From 1912\u201314 he was Chairman of the Insurance Committee for the County of London,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://1914-1918.invisionzone.com/forums/lofiversion/index.php/t19863.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-01-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203202845/http://1914-1918.invisionzone.com/forums/lofiversion/index.php/t19863.html |archivedate=3 February 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> created to administer the medical aspects of the [[National Insurance Act 1911|National Insurance Act of 1911]], which for the first time established compulsory contributory insurance against illness and unemployment for workers.<ref name=\"Who was Who, OUP 2007\" /> Dawes Street, London SE 17 was named after him to commemorate his appointment as the first Mayor of the Borough of Southwark.<ref>Adrian Room, ''The Street Names of England''; Paul Watkins, 1992 p157</ref>\n\n== Parliament ==\nBy 1908 Dawes had been selected as prospective Liberal candidate for [[Newington Walworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Walworth]] <ref>The Times, 14 December 1908 p5</ref> in succession to [[Charles James O'Donnell]] who had decided not to contest the next election. Dawes was duly elected as Liberal MP for [[Newington Walworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Walworth]] at the general election of  [[January 1910 United Kingdom general election|January 1910]]. He held the seat with a slightly increased majority in [[December 1910 United Kingdom general election|December 1910]].<ref>''The Times House of Commons 1911'', Politico\u2019s Publishing 2004 p27</ref> In 1918 his constituency disappeared in boundary changes but he was selected for the new local constituency of [[Southwark South East (UK Parliament constituency)|Southwark South East]]. He fought the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918 general election]] as a Coalition Liberal, that is as a supporter of the [[Coalition Government 1916\u20131922|Coalition Government]] of [[Prime Minister]] [[David Lloyd George]]. He presumably received the [[Coalition Coupon]] because he was not opposed by a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Unionist]] candidate and won in a straight fight with [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]].<ref>F W S Craig, ''British Parliamentary Election Results 1918\u20131949''; Political Reference Publications, Glasgow, 1914 p50</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nOn 9 November 1921 Dawes was chosen as Mayor of [[Dartmouth, Devon|Dartmouth]] in [[Devon]] where he had his country home.<ref>The Times, 10 November 1921 p12</ref> His appointment was not to last long however as he died on 14 November 1921 at [[Sydenham, London|Sydenham]] at the age of 55 years.<ref>The Times, 15 November 1921 p1</ref> His death caused a [[1921 Southwark South East by-election|by-election in Southwark]] which was won by [[Thomas Naylor (UK politician)|Thomas Ellis Naylor]] for Labour. Dawes was buried in the churchyard at [[Perivale]], a suburb of Ealing.\n\n== Works ==\nDawes wrote two associated pamphlets on National Insurance for the Liberal Party.\n* ''National Health Insurance: Part 1 of the National Insurance Act 1911'' \u2013 Liberal Publications Dept, 1912\n* ''National Health Insurance: Part 2 of the National Insurance Act 1911'' \u2013 Liberal Publications Dept, 1912\n\nDawes also published a ''Dissertation on the Law of Partnership'' in 1909 and was a co-author of the ''Report of the National Committee to Promote the Break-up of the Poor Law'' in 1910.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{hansard-contribs | mr-james-dawes | James Dawes}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Charles James O'Donnell]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Walworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Walworth]]\n | years = [[January 1910 United Kingdom general election|January 1910]] \u2013 [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]]\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished }}\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Southwark South East (UK Parliament constituency)|Southwark South East]]\n | years = [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]] \u2013 [[1921 Southwark South East by-election|1921]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Thomas Naylor (UK politician)|Thomas Naylor]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dawes, James Arthur}}\n[[Category:1866 births]]\n[[Category:1921 deaths]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1918\u20131922]]\n[[Category:Members of London County Council]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Greater London]]\n[[Category:English solicitors]]\n[[Category:People educated at Harrow School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:People from Ealing]]\n[[Category:Members of Southwark Metropolitan Borough Council]]\n[[Category:Politics of Devon]]\n[[Category:Progressive Party (London) politicians]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy officers of World War I]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n[[File:James Arthur Dawes.jpg|thumb|right|James Arthur Dawes]]\n'''James Arthur Dawes''' (16 June 1866 \u2013 14 November 1921) was an English [[solicitor]], businessman and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) from 1910 to 1921.\n\n== Family and education ==\nJames Arthur Dawes was the son of Richard Dawes of Castle Hill, [[Ealing]], [[Middlesex]], a solicitor in Angel Court, [[Throgmorton Street]], London. He was educated at [[Harrow School]] and [[University College, Oxford]] where he gained [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|MA]] and [[Bachelor of Civil Law]] degrees. In 1920 he married Violet Pridmore from [[Penge]] in [[Surrey]].<ref name=\"Who was Who, OUP 2007\">''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref> They do not appear to have had children.\n\n== Career ==\nDawes qualified as a solicitor in 1891 <ref>The Times, 31 January 1891 p13 & 21 November 1891 p10</ref> and was admitted to his father\u2019s firm, Mssrs. Dawes and Sons, in January 1892 <ref>The Times, 8 January 1892 p9</ref> He was later a [[Justice of the Peace]] for the [[County of London]].<ref name=\"Who was Who, OUP 2007\" /> From the outset of the First World War, Dawes served with the [[Royal Naval Reserve]] and [[Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve]] raising to the rank of acting [[Commander (Royal Navy)|Commander]] by 1918.<ref name=\"Who was Who, OUP 2007\" /> He was engaged in mine-sweeping operations and from July 1918 he served at the [[Admiralty]].<ref>The Times, 12 December 1918 p9</ref> Unsurprisingly, one of Dawes recreations was [[yachting]].<ref name=\"Who was Who, OUP 2007\" />\n\n== Southwark and London Politics ==\nDawes had a home in [[Kennington Park Road]] in [[Southwark]]. He took a strong interest in local affairs <ref>''The Times House of Commons 1910'', Politico\u2019s Publishing 2004 p26</ref> and was Chairman of the Vestry of Newington, the equivalent of a [[Parish councils in England|Parish council]], from 1897\u20131900. Dawes was then the first [[Mayor]] of the [[Metropolitan Borough of Southwark|Borough of Southwark]] from 1900\u20131901 and Deputy Mayor the following year.<ref>The Times, 5 September 1902 p11</ref> He was re-elected Mayor in 1913\u201314 <ref>The Times, 11 November 1913 p4</ref> and 1914\u201315. He also served as a founder member of the [[Metropolitan Water Board (London)|Metropolitan Water Board]] in 1903\u20131904. He was later elected as a member of the [[London County Council]] for the [[Progressive Party (London)|Progressive Party]] for  Newington Walworth for various years between 1906 and 1913.<ref>The Times, 4 March 1907 p6; 7 March 19109, p7; 7 March 1913, p9</ref> In 1911 Dawes was appointed to the Joint Committee of the two Houses of Parliament to consider the Bill promoted by the Metropolitan Water Board to construct a series of new works and reservoirs on the [[River Thames]] at [[Staines]].<ref>The Times, 31 March 1911 p4</ref>  From 1912\u201314 he was Chairman of the Insurance Committee for the County of London,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://1914-1918.invisionzone.com/forums/lofiversion/index.php/t19863.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-01-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203202845/http://1914-1918.invisionzone.com/forums/lofiversion/index.php/t19863.html |archivedate=3 February 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> created to administer the medical aspects of the [[National Insurance Act 1911|National Insurance Act of 1911]], which for the first time established compulsory contributory insurance against illness and unemployment for workers.<ref name=\"Who was Who, OUP 2007\" /> Dawes Street, London SE 17 was named after him to commemorate his appointment as the first Mayor of the Borough of Southwark.<ref>Adrian Room, ''The Street Names of England''; Paul Watkins, 1992 p157</ref>\n\n== Parliament ==\nBy 1908 Dawes had been selected as prospective Liberal candidate for [[Newington Walworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Walworth]] <ref>The Times, 14 December 1908 p5</ref> in succession to [[Charles James O'Donnell]] who had decided not to contest the next election. Dawes was duly elected as Liberal MP for [[Newington Walworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Walworth]] at the general election of  [[January 1910 United Kingdom general election|January 1910]]. He held the seat with a slightly increased majority in [[December 1910 United Kingdom general election|December 1910]].<ref>''The Times House of Commons 1911'', Politico\u2019s Publishing 2004 p27</ref> In 1918 his constituency disappeared in boundary changes but he was selected for the new local constituency of [[Southwark South East (UK Parliament constituency)|Southwark South East]]. He fought the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918 general election]] as a Coalition Liberal, that is as a supporter of the [[Coalition Government 1916\u20131922|Coalition Government]] of [[Prime Minister]] [[David Lloyd George]]. He presumably received the [[Coalition Coupon]] because he was not opposed by a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Unionist]] candidate and won in a straight fight with [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]].<ref>F W S Craig, ''British Parliamentary Election Results 1918\u20131949''; Political Reference Publications, Glasgow, 1914 p50</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nOn 9 November 1921 Dawes was chosen as Mayor of [[Dartmouth, Devon|Dartmouth]] in [[Devon]] where he had his country home.<ref>The Times, 10 November 1921 p12</ref> His appointment was not to last long however as he died on 14 November 1921 at [[Sydenham, London|Sydenham]] at the age of 55 years.<ref>The Times, 15 November 1921 p1</ref> His death caused a [[1921 Southwark South East by-election|by-election in Southwark]] which was won by [[Thomas Naylor (UK politician)|Thomas Ellis Naylor]] for Labour. Dawes was buried in the churchyard at [[Perivale]], a suburb of Ealing.\n\n== Works ==\nDawes wrote two associated pamphlets on National Insurance for the Liberal Party.\n* ''National Health Insurance: Part 1 of the National Insurance Act 1911'' \u2013 Liberal Publications Dept, 1912\n* ''National Health Insurance: Part 2 of the National Insurance Act 1911'' \u2013 Liberal Publications Dept, 1912\n\nDawes also published a ''Dissertation on the Law of Partnership'' in 1909 and was a co-author of the ''Report of the National Committee to Promote the Break-up of the Poor Law'' in 1910.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{hansard-contribs | mr-james-dawes | James Dawes}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Charles James O'Donnell]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Walworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Walworth]]\n | years = [[January 1910 United Kingdom general election|January 1910]] \u2013 [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]]\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished }}\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Southwark South East (UK Parliament constituency)|Southwark South East]]\n | years = [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]] \u2013 [[1921 Southwark South East by-election|1921]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Thomas Naylor (UK politician)|Thomas Naylor]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dawes, James Arthur}}\n[[Category:1866 births]]\n[[Category:1921 deaths]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1918\u20131922]]\n[[Category:Members of London County Council]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Greater London]]\n[[Category:English solicitors]]\n[[Category:People educated at Harrow School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:People from Ealing]]\n[[Category:Members of Southwark Metropolitan Borough Council]]\n[[Category:Politics of Devon]]\n[[Category:Progressive Party (London) politicians]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy officers of World War I]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Dawes_(British_politician)"}
{"title_page": "Basque Summer University", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Markeskoa Eibar Dorreagaz.jpg|thumb|Palace of Markeskua in [[Eibar]]. Headquarters of the Basque Summer University.]]\nThe '''Basque Summer University''' (in Basque and officially: '''Udako Euskal Unibertsitatea''', <u>'''UEU'''</u>) is a university institution created in 1973, which offers university courses in collaboration with the [[University of the Basque Country]], [[Mondragon University]], [[Public University of Navarre|Public University of Navarra]], the [[University of Pau and Pays de l'Adour]] in [[Bayonne]], and [[Basque Wikipedia]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oecd.org/education/skills-beyond-school/Basque%20Country%20Self%20Evaluation%20Report.pdf|title=The Basque Country, Spain: Self-Evaluation Report. OECD Reviews of Higher Education in Regional and City Development|last=Martinez-Granado|first=Maite|last2=Gere\u00f1o|first2=Patxi|year=2012|website=OECD Reviews of Higher Education in Regional and City Development|url-status=live|last3=Oleaga|first3=Mercedes}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.etxepare.eus/en/learn-basque|title=Learn Basque {{!}} Etxepare Basque Institute|website=www.etxepare.eus|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://combiproject.eu/combi-course-in-eibar/|title=A COMBI course in Eibar (Basque Country) \u2013 July 2019 {{!}} COMBI|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://outreach.wikimedia.org/wiki/Education/News/July_2017/Wikipedia_in_the_UEU_Basque_Summer_University|title=Education/News/July 2017/Wikipedia in the UEU Basque Summer University \u2013 Outreach Wiki|website=outreach.wikimedia.org|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Basque_Wikimedians_User_Group/Reports/2017|title=Basque Wikimedians User Group/Reports/2017 \u2013 Meta|website=meta.wikimedia.org|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe '''UEU''' has its headquarters in the Palace of Markeskua ([[Eibar]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tourism.euskadi.eus/en/cultural-heritage/isasi-palace-markeskua/aa30-12375/en/|title=Isasi Palace (Markeskua)|last=Basque Government|date=11 January 2007|website=tourism.euskadi.eus|url-status=live|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref> Although its name is the Basque Summer University (Udako Euskal Unibertsitatea, UEU), the institution offers university courses year-round, not just in the summer. It is currently a non-profit organisation and in 1990 it was recognised as a public utility organisation because it promotes general interest in the field of research, learning, and dissemination, mainly at university level, through the many pedagogical and cultural services it provides.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Basque Government|date=6 November 1990|title=\"Decree 280/1990. Recognition of Public Utility to the association \"Udako Euskal Unibertsitatea, UEU\" of Bilbao.|url=https://www.euskadi.eus/bopv2/datos/1990/11/9003277a.pdf|journal=Official Gazette of the Basque Country. Euskal Herriko Aldizkari Ofiziala.|volume=1990-11-16|pages=10004}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n==== Background: No university education in Basque until 1972 ====\nAfter examining the continuing historical regression of the geographical environment where Basque was spoken, the linguist [[Wilhelm von Humboldt|Wilhem von Humboldt]] predicted in 1809 that this language might disappear in less than a century from the list of living languages.\n\nThe social, economic, political and cultural processes set in motion by industrialisation and liberalism during the 19th century led to an even greater decline in Basque. As a fact, it suffices to say that Basque remained on the margin of the school, where even its use became forbidden.\n\nAmong the initiatives that emerged in the 20th century to deal with the risk of the disappearance of Basque are the creation of the [[Society of Basque Studies]] and the [[Euskaltzaindia|Royal Academy of the Basque Language]] (Euskaltzaindia) in 1919 and the creation of [[Ikastola]]s (schools in Basque), initially in the 1930s and later in the 1960s.\n\n==== Background: creation of the unified Basque language in 1968 ====\nBasque, which has 7 main dialects, did not have a standard model of writing until 1968, when Euskaltzaindia laid the foundations of the unified Basque (in Basque ''batua''). Historically, apart from specific and brief exceptions, until then there had never been any training in Basque at university level and in 1972 it was still impossible to study any university degree or even any subject in Basque.\n\n==== Creation of the UEU in 1973 ====\nIn this context, the history of the UEU began in the Basque Weeks organised in [[Bayonne]] during the years 1970\u20131972. Seeing the success of these days and the discourse given by the mathematician Carlos Santamar\u00eda Ansa on the need to create a Basque University, the Euskaldunen Biltzarra, Ikas and Fededunak associations decided to organise summer courses in 1973 with the support of Euskaltzaindia. Similar initiatives that already existed for [[Catalan language|Catalan]] and [[Occitan language|Occitan]] served as antecedents and references; for example, the Universitat Catalana d'Estiu had been in operation since 1968. [[Joxe Azurmendi]] was one of the founders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n50058090.html|title=LC Linked Data Service: Authorities and Vocabularies (Library of Congress)|last=Congress|first=The Library of|website=id.loc.gov|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first two editions of the UEU (1973 and 1974) were held in [[Saint-Jean-de-Luz|St. Jean de Luz]] and the next two (1975 and 1976) in [[Ustaritz]].\n\n==== Summer courses in Pamplona (1977\u20131999) ====\nIn 1977 the summer courses of the UEU moved to [[Pamplona]], becoming year after year the meeting point that allowed the training of teachers and the creation of materials that were incorporated in the offer of new subjects of the official universities. Over the years, it offered between 40 and 50 summer courses each year. For example, in 1995 it offered 45 courses distributed in 26 departments; in total there were 750 teaching hours, in classes, practices, seminars and outings, with more than 650 participants. Annually, UEU published an average of 10 books. The number of teachers and students who worked in Basque at university level in that year would not exceed 4,000 people, and of all of them more than 650 participated in the UEU, this being proof of the success and contribution of these courses, in spite of the limited economic resources it had.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bertan.gipuzkoakultura.net/24/ing/16.php|title=Bertan 24 \u2013 The basque language Chapter 15: Consolidation of the basque language|website=bertan.gipuzkoakultura.net|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Present situation ====\nSince 1999 these university level courses began to develop not only in summer and in Pamplona, but also throughout the year and in multiple locations. After almost 50 years, thanks to this social process promoted and led by the UEU, it has been possible to take some significant steps in the inclusion of Basque in the university. For example, in 2019 almost all university degrees can also be studied in Basque at one of the universities in the Basque Country; more than 400 books have been published in Basque on 27 university disciplines; congresses are regularly organised in Basque for professionals and academics... The UEU collaborates and offers university courses with the other universities in the Basque Country: the University of the Basque Country, the University of Mondrag\u00f3n, the University of Deusto, the Public University of Navarra, and the University of Pau and Pays de l'Adur.\n\nThe UEU is currently headquartered in the Markeskua Palace (Eibar) and has 1,200 members. It organises training in Basque at university level in different formats: postgraduate courses, specialised courses, seminars, professional congresses (e.g. Computer Science congresses, Informatikari Euskaldunen Bilkurak), training aimed at teachers and professionals, summer courses and research projects related to the above (master...); it also offers postgraduate studies.a m\n\nThe UEU offers studies in the Basque Autonomous Community, in Navarre and in the French Basque Country, with the UEU's objective being to promote a quality Basque-speaking university throughout the territory where Basque language is used.  According to this approach, achieving a university that works in Basque would be a fundamental element so that the forecast made by Humboldt is not fulfilled and Basque continues for many years in the list of living languages. Furthermore, the experience gained with Basque could be a reference for the preservation of other minority languages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unibertsitatea.net/basque-speaking-university-community|title=Basque-speaking university community \u2013 Unibertsitatea.Net|website=unibertsitatea.net|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Rectors of the UEU have been the following: Manex Goihenetxe (1973\u20131976), Martin Orbe (1976\u20131983), Baleren Bakaikoa (1983\u20131987), Inaki Irazabalbeitia (1987\u20131991), Kepa Altonaga (1991\u20131996), Mikel Aizpuru (1996\u20132000), Xabier Isasi (2000\u20132004), Aitzpea Leizaola (2004\u20132005), Lore Erriondo (2005\u20132010), Karmele Artetxe (2010\u20132014), I\u00f1aki Alegr\u00eda (2014\u20132018) eta Kepa Sarasola (2018\u2013).\n\n== Publications ==\nThe UEU published its first book in 1977, since then until 2018 it has published 419, more or less 10 books per year. In the field of book publishing, since its inception the UEU has pursued two objectives: on the one hand, to create a bibliographic infrastructure at university level, and on the other, to refine the [[terminology]] and [[syntax]] in [[Basque language|Basque]]. The electronic version of most of the more than 400 books published by the UEU are publicly accessible in its digital library ''Buruxkak''.\n\nIn addition to books, since 2003 it also publishes academic journals. In 2018 there were four journals: ''Uztaro'', about social sciences and created in 1990; ''Aldiri, Arkitektura eta abar'', about architecture and created in 2009; ''Osagaiz'', about health sciences and created in 2017; and finally ''Kondaira'', about history created in 2003.\n== Postgraduate degrees and own degrees ==\nBeginning in 2001 and in collaboration with the University of the Basque Country, the UEU has taught 14 own degrees or postgraduates, of which more than 240 students have graduated.  For example in 2018, two courses were given; one on \"Translation and technology\" and the other on \"the use of new technologies in education\".\n\n== Training courses ==\nSince its creation in 1973, the UEU has delivered more than 1,900 training courses at university level.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.inguma.eus/bilatu/bilaketa-aurreratua?egilea=&izenburua=&produktu_mota=&shu=&urtea=&erakundea=UEU&fakultatea=&ueu_saila=&Bilatu=Bilatu&mota=course&page=1&hizkuntza=en|title=Courses given by the Basque Summer University. Advanced search Inguma Database of the basque scientific community.|last=UEU|date=15 November 2019|website=inguma.eus|url-status=live|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref> Online courses began to be delivered in 2003. The first MOOC course (''Introduction to Android programming / Android programazioaren hastapenak'') took place in 2013. The courses have always been organized from the thematic sections of the UEU, which are the following: Anthropology, Theater,  Architecture, Art, Bertsolaritza, Economy, Philosophy, Physics, Glotodidactics, History of Linguistics, Informatics, Translation, Journalism, Chemistry, Climatology and Meteorology, Literature, Mathematics, Music, Natural Sciences, Health Sciences, Pedagogy, Psychology, Sexology, Sociolinguistics, Sociology, and Law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Basque_Wikimedians_User_Group/Reports/2018|title=Basque Wikimedians User Group/Reports/2018 \u2013 Meta|website=meta.wikimedia.org|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.soziolinguistika.eus/files/thecaseof_basque-1.pdf|title=The case of Basque. Past, Present and Future.|last=Azurmendi|first=Maria_Jose|last2=Martinez de LUna|first2=I\u00f1aki|year=2005|website=Soziolinguistikako klusterra|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.domeinuak.eus/en/new/the-pilot-edition-of-the-kaixomundua-eus-competition-was-held-successfully/|title=The pilot edition of the kaixomundua.eus competition was held successfully|website=Domeinuak .eus|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tabakalera.eu/en/geomatics-and-spatial-intelligence|title=Geomatics and spatial intelligence|date=23 October 2017|website=tabakalera.eu|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Databases and Internet services ==\nThe UEU has created several databases and Internet services associated with new technologies to respond to training needs and to serve to the university community in Basque: \n\n*''Inguma'': database on the production of the Basque scientific community. Inguma is a source of information about everything that has been produced orally and in written form in Basque within the academic world since 1968 when the guidelines that led to the unification of the unified Basque language began to be set. In 2018, in total, it included cataloguing. There are both written documents (books, articles, prologues, reviews, translations, critical editions, research projects, doctoral theses) and oral documents summer         (conferences, courses, meetings, conferences, subjects).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.inguma.eus/ingumari-buruz/en|title=About Inguma. What is Inguma? Basque scientific-intellectual community|last=UEU|year=2000|website=inguma.eus|url-status=live|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n*''Artizarra'' social network for professionals and researchers.\n*''Buruxkak''. The digital library of the UEU, in 2018 it was offering the digital versions of 390 books from among the 419 published by this entity.\n*''Otarrea''. A compilation of works, reports, notes, and other types of university documents to be shared freely under a Creative Commons license. In 2018 it contained 941 documents distributed by fields in this way: Art and music (4), Humanities (112), Social sciences (333), Engineering and technology (393), Health sciences (19), Applied sciences (2) and Sciences (78).\n*''Tesiker'', PhD theses in Basque. The Tesiker database offers information and access to more than 450 theses that have been published in Basque. This web service is offered from the [[Basque Government]]'s website after having been collected by the UEU.\n*''Unibertsitatea.net'', meeting place and point of reference for anyone associated with or interested in the university, such as students, teaching staff, researchers, parents, members of the press, etc.university community portal. It publishes news about the Basque university community (including 140 interviews with young researchers, and 10 blogs (economy, Language processing, Art, Environment...).<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Iparrorratza'', orientation for university access. The Iparrorratza service offers a counselling service for young people entering university to help them choose their studies.\n\n== Building the community of young researchers ==\nSince 2012, the UEU has promoted the creation of a community of young researchers with the aim of promoting multidisciplinary knowledge and exchange. Three of its most relevant activities are the following:\n*''Ikergazte'' Congress (in Basque; Iker (research) gazte(young)) This congress has been held every two years since 2015. The number of participants was always greater than 200 and more than 120 articles were presented.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ueu.eus/ikergazte/en/|title=Third Conference for Basque young researchers. Ikergazte. Baiona 27\u201329 May 2019|last=UEU|date=27 May 2019|website=Ikergazte|url-status=live|archive-url=live|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n*''Txiotesia'' Competition. With the same objective of promoting mutual knowledge, since 2012, this competition has been organized biennially. Participants describe their doctoral thesis work in just 6 tweets.\n* Web portal with interviews, The portal ''unibertsitatea.net'' has interviewed more than 120 young researchers.\n\n==Other universities operating in the Basque Country==\n*[[University of the Basque Country]]\n*[[University of Pau and the Adour region]]\n*[[University of Deusto]]\n*[[National University of Distance Education]]\n*[[University of Navarre]]\n*[[Universidad P\u00fablica de Navarra]]\n*[[Mondragon University]]\n*[[Musikene]]\n\n==Similar entities operating with other minority languages==\nThe following entities are similar to the UEU in that they work to promote the extensive use of a minority language at the university level:\n\n=== Catalan ===\n\n* The Catalan Summer University, ''Universitat Catalana d'Estiu'' (UCE) in Catalan language and officially. It is a summer university in Catalan language that takes place annually in the French town of [[Prades, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Orientales|Prades]]. It was founded in the summer of 1968, just after the events of May 1968.\n\n=== Irish ===\n\n*Fiontar is in Dublin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dcu.ie/fiontar_scoilnagaeilge/english/index.shtml|title=Fiontar Home \u2013 English Version {{!}} DCU|website=www.dcu.ie|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Acadamh na hOllscola\u00edochta Gaeilge|Acadamh na hOllscola\u00edochta]] is based in the [[West of Ireland]]. Its main campus is in the [[National University of Ireland, Galway|National University of Ireland]] in [[Galway]] City and it also has three other locations around the West of Ireland. They provide courses at different levels: degrees and postgraduate courses as well as diplomas and other short courses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nuigalway.ie/acadamh/eolasfuinn/|title=Eolas F\u00fainn \u2013 NUI Galway|website=nuigalway.ie|language=ga|url-status=live|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Col\u00e1iste na h\u00c9ireann]] (English: \"College of Ireland\") is a [[Tertiary education|third-level college]] in [[Dublin]], offering qualifications in the study of [[translation]] and the [[Irish language]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730203508/https://www.chg.gov.ie/ga/gaeltacht/the-irish-language/language-support-schemes/third-level-education-in-ireland/|title=Oideachas Tr\u00ed\u00fa Leibh\u00e9al in \u00c9irinn {{!}} An Roinn Cult\u00fair, Oidhreachta agus Gaeltachta|date=2019-07-30|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730203618/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/education/make-yourself-employable-with-a-postgrad-as-gaeilge-1.2560311|title=Make yourself employable with a postgrad as Gaeilge|date=2019-07-30|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Welsh ===\n\n* [[Coleg Cymraeg Cenedlaethol|Coleg Cymraeg ''Cenedlaethol'']] (in English: Welsh National College). It is known in both [[Welsh language|Welsh]] and English simply as ''Coleg''. It was established in 2011 by the [[Welsh Government]] to work with [[List of universities in Wales|universities in Wales]] to develop Welsh-language courses and resources for students; it also provides and advances Welsh medium courses, scholarship and research in Welsh universities. It works through branches in Welsh Universities to enable more opportunities to study for Welsh medium students in partnership with the universities.  Its aim is to increase the number of students who choose to study part or all of their course in Welsh.  It funds under- and post-graduate scholarships, sponsors Welsh medium lecturers and supports students who study in Welsh.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.colegcymraeg.ac.uk/cy/|title=Y Coleg Cymraeg Cenedlaethol|website=colegcymraeg.ac.uk|language=cy|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n*Y Gymdeithas Feddygol (Welsh language medical society) \u2013 supports the right to receive healthcare in Welsh and cooperates with any organisation to deliver it.  It encourages Welsh medium healthcare studies and gives opportunities to present their work in Welsh.  It gives opportunities for students and doctors to network in our annual conferences and the National Eisteddfod.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ygymdeithasfeddygol.cymru/|title=Cartref|website=Y Gymdeithas Feddygol|language=cy|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}{{Commons category}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[University of the Basque Country]]\n*[[Coleg Cymraeg Cenedlaethol|Coleg Cymraeg]]\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.ueu.eus/who-are-we Official website]\n*[http://www.inguma.eus/ingumari-buruz/en Inguma], database on the production of the Basque scientific community.\n*[http://www.buruxkak.eus/ Buruxkak], digital library of the Basque Summer University. More than 400 books published by the Basque Summer University.(in Basque)\n*[https://www.artizarra.eus/ Artizarra.eus], profesional social network. {{in lang|eu}}\n*[http://www.euskadi.eus/web01-apdoktes/eu/w10aTesDocWar/comunJSP/w10aPrincipal.do?idioma=eu Tesiker], database of PhD theses written in Basque {{in lang|eu|es}}\n*[https://www.unibertsitatea.net/blogak/ unibertsitatea.net], website of the university community in Basque (news, blogs...){{in lang|eu}}\n\n{{coord missing|France}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Spain]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in France]]\n[[Category:Basque culture]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Markeskoa Eibar Dorreagaz.jpg|thumb|Palace of Markeskua in [[Eibar]]. Headquarters of the Basque Summer University.]]\nThe '''Basque Summer University''' (in Basque and officially: '''Udako Euskal Unibertsitatea''', <u>'''UEU'''</u>) is a university institution created in 1973, which offers university courses in collaboration with the [[University of the Basque Country]], [[Mondragon University]], [[Public University of Navarre|Public University of Navarra]], the [[University of Pau and Pays de l'Adour]] in [[Bayonne]], and [[Basque Wikipedia]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oecd.org/education/skills-beyond-school/Basque%20Country%20Self%20Evaluation%20Report.pdf|title=The Basque Country, Spain: Self-Evaluation Report. OECD Reviews of Higher Education in Regional and City Development|last=Martinez-Granado|first=Maite|last2=Gere\u00f1o|first2=Patxi|year=2012|website=OECD Reviews of Higher Education in Regional and City Development|url-status=live|last3=Oleaga|first3=Mercedes}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.etxepare.eus/en/learn-basque|title=Learn Basque {{!}} Etxepare Basque Institute|website=www.etxepare.eus|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://combiproject.eu/combi-course-in-eibar/|title=A COMBI course in Eibar (Basque Country) \u2013 July 2019 {{!}} COMBI|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://outreach.wikimedia.org/wiki/Education/News/July_2017/Wikipedia_in_the_UEU_Basque_Summer_University|title=Education/News/July 2017/Wikipedia in the UEU Basque Summer University \u2013 Outreach Wiki|website=outreach.wikimedia.org|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Basque_Wikimedians_User_Group/Reports/2017|title=Basque Wikimedians User Group/Reports/2017 \u2013 Meta|website=meta.wikimedia.org|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe '''UEU''' has its headquarters in the Palace of Markeskua ([[Eibar]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tourism.euskadi.eus/en/cultural-heritage/isasi-palace-markeskua/aa30-12375/en/|title=Isasi Palace (Markeskua)|last=Basque Government|date=11 January 2007|website=tourism.euskadi.eus|url-status=live|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref> Although its name is the Basque Summer University (Udako Euskal Unibertsitatea, UEU), the institution offers university courses year-round, not just in the summer. It is currently a non-profit organisation and in 1990 it was recognised as a public utility organisation because it promotes general interest in the field of research, learning, and dissemination, mainly at university level, through the many pedagogical and cultural services it provides.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Basque Government|date=6 November 1990|title=\"Decree 280/1990. Recognition of Public Utility to the association \"Udako Euskal Unibertsitatea, UEU\" of Bilbao.|url=https://www.euskadi.eus/bopv2/datos/1990/11/9003277a.pdf|journal=Official Gazette of the Basque Country. Euskal Herriko Aldizkari Ofiziala.|volume=1990-11-16|pages=10004}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n==== Background: No university education in Basque until 1972 ====\nAfter examining the continuing historical regression of the geographical environment where Basque was spoken, the linguist [[Wilhelm von Humboldt|Wilhem von Humboldt]] predicted in 1809 that this language might disappear in less than a century from the list of living languages.\n\nThe social, economic, political and cultural processes set in motion by industrialisation and liberalism during the 19th century led to an even greater decline in Basque. As a fact, it suffices to say that Basque remained on the margin of the school, where even its use became forbidden.\n\nAmong the initiatives that emerged in the 20th century to deal with the risk of the disappearance of Basque are the creation of the [[Society of Basque Studies]] and the [[Euskaltzaindia|Royal Academy of the Basque Language]] (Euskaltzaindia) in 1919 and the creation of [[Ikastola]]s (schools in Basque), initially in the 1930s and later in the 1960s.\n\n==== Background: creation of the unified Basque language in 1968 ====\nBasque, which has 7 main dialects, did not have a standard model of writing until 1968, when Euskaltzaindia laid the foundations of the unified Basque (in Basque ''batua''). Historically, apart from specific and brief exceptions, until then there had never been any training in Basque at university level and in 1972 it was still impossible to study any university degree or even any subject in Basque.\n\n==== Creation of the UEU in 1973 ====\nIn this context, the history of the UEU began in the Basque Weeks organised in [[Bayonne]] during the years 1970\u20131972. Seeing the success of these days and the discourse given by the mathematician Carlos Santamar\u00eda Ansa on the need to create a Basque University, the Euskaldunen Biltzarra, Ikas and Fededunak associations decided to organise summer courses in 1973 with the support of Euskaltzaindia. Similar initiatives that already existed for [[Catalan language|Catalan]] and [[Occitan language|Occitan]] served as antecedents and references; for example, the Universitat Catalana d'Estiu had been in operation since 1968. [[Joxe Azurmendi]] was one of the founders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n50058090.html|title=LC Linked Data Service: Authorities and Vocabularies (Library of Congress)|last=Congress|first=The Library of|website=id.loc.gov|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first two editions of the UEU (1973 and 1974) were held in [[Saint-Jean-de-Luz|St. Jean de Luz]] and the next two (1975 and 1976) in [[Ustaritz]].\n\n==== Summer courses in Pamplona (1977\u20131999) ====\nIn 1977 the summer courses of the UEU moved to [[Pamplona]], becoming year after year the meeting point that allowed the training of teachers and the creation of materials that were incorporated in the offer of new subjects of the official universities. Over the years, it offered between 40 and 50 summer courses each year. For example, in 1995 it offered 45 courses distributed in 26 departments; in total there were 750 teaching hours, in classes, practices, seminars and outings, with more than 650 participants. Annually, UEU published an average of 10 books. The number of teachers and students who worked in Basque at university level in that year would not exceed 4,000 people, and of all of them more than 650 participated in the UEU, this being proof of the success and contribution of these courses, in spite of the limited economic resources it had.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bertan.gipuzkoakultura.net/24/ing/16.php|title=Bertan 24 \u2013 The basque language Chapter 15: Consolidation of the basque language|website=bertan.gipuzkoakultura.net|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Present situation ====\nSince 1999 these university level courses began to develop not only in summer and in Pamplona, but also throughout the year and in multiple locations. After almost 50 years, thanks to this social process promoted and led by the UEU, it has been possible to take some significant steps in the inclusion of Basque in the university. For example, in 2019 almost all university degrees can also be studied in Basque at one of the universities in the Basque Country; more than 400 books have been published in Basque on 27 university disciplines; congresses are regularly organised in Basque for professionals and academics... The UEU collaborates and offers university courses with the other universities in the Basque Country: the University of the Basque Country, the University of Mondrag\u00f3n, the University of Deusto, the Public University of Navarra, and the University of Pau and Pays de l'Adur.\n\nThe UEU is currently headquartered in the Markeskua Palace (Eibar) and has 1,200 members. It organises training in Basque at university level in different formats: postgraduate courses, specialised courses, seminars, professional congresses (e.g. Computer Science congresses, Informatikari Euskaldunen Bilkurak), training aimed at teachers and professionals, summer courses and research projects related to the above (master...); it also offers postgraduate studies.a m\n\nThe UEU offers studies in the Basque Autonomous Community, in Navarre and in the French Basque Country, with the UEU's objective being to promote a quality Basque-speaking university throughout the territory where Basque language is used.  According to this approach, achieving a university that works in Basque would be a fundamental element so that the forecast made by Humboldt is not fulfilled and Basque continues for many years in the list of living languages. Furthermore, the experience gained with Basque could be a reference for the preservation of other minority languages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unibertsitatea.net/basque-speaking-university-community|title=Basque-speaking university community \u2013 Unibertsitatea.Net|website=unibertsitatea.net|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Rectors of the UEU have been the following: Manex Goihenetxe (1973\u20131976), Martin Orbe (1976\u20131983), Baleren Bakaikoa (1983\u20131987), Inaki Irazabalbeitia (1987\u20131991), Kepa Altonaga (1991\u20131996), Mikel Aizpuru (1996\u20132000), Xabier Isasi (2000\u20132004), Aitzpea Leizaola (2004\u20132005), Lore Erriondo (2005\u20132010), Karmele Artetxe (2010\u20132014), I\u00f1aki Alegr\u00eda (2014\u20132018) eta Kepa Sarasola (2018\u2013).\n\n== Publications ==\nThe UEU published its first book in 1977, since then until 2018 it has published 419, more or less 10 books per year. In the field of book publishing, since its inception the UEU has pursued two objectives: on the one hand, to create a bibliographic infrastructure at university level, and on the other, to refine the [[terminology]] and [[syntax]] in [[Basque language|Basque]]. The electronic version of most of the more than 400 books published by the UEU are publicly accessible in its digital library ''Buruxkak''.\n\nIn addition to books, since 2003 it also publishes academic journals. In 2018 there were four journals: ''Uztaro'', about social sciences and created in 1990; ''Aldiri, Arkitektura eta abar'', about architecture and created in 2009; ''Osagaiz'', about health sciences and created in 2017; and finally ''Kondaira'', about history created in 2003.\n== Postgraduate degrees and own degrees ==\nBeginning in 2001 and in collaboration with the University of the Basque Country, the UEU has taught 14 own degrees or postgraduates, of which more than 240 students have graduated.  For example in 2018, two courses were given; one on \"Translation and technology\" and the other on \"the use of new technologies in education\".\n\n== Training courses ==\nSince its creation in 1973, the UEU has delivered more than 1,900 training courses at university level.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.inguma.eus/bilatu/bilaketa-aurreratua?egilea=&izenburua=&produktu_mota=&shu=&urtea=&erakundea=UEU&fakultatea=&ueu_saila=&Bilatu=Bilatu&mota=course&page=1&hizkuntza=en|title=Courses given by the Basque Summer University. Advanced search Inguma Database of the basque scientific community.|last=UEU|date=15 November 2019|website=inguma.eus|url-status=live|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref> Online courses began to be delivered in 2003. The first MOOC course (''Introduction to Android programming / Android programazioaren hastapenak'') took place in 2013. The courses have always been organized from the thematic sections of the UEU, which are the following: Anthropology, Theater,  Architecture, Art, Bertsolaritza, Economy, Philosophy, Physics, Glotodidactics, History of Linguistics, Informatics, Translation, Journalism, Chemistry, Climatology and Meteorology, Literature, Mathematics, Music, Natural Sciences, Health Sciences, Pedagogy, Psychology, Sexology, Sociolinguistics, Sociology, and Law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Basque_Wikimedians_User_Group/Reports/2018|title=Basque Wikimedians User Group/Reports/2018 \u2013 Meta|website=meta.wikimedia.org|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.soziolinguistika.eus/files/thecaseof_basque-1.pdf|title=The case of Basque. Past, Present and Future.|last=Azurmendi|first=Maria_Jose|last2=Martinez de LUna|first2=I\u00f1aki|year=2005|website=Soziolinguistikako klusterra|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.domeinuak.eus/en/new/the-pilot-edition-of-the-kaixomundua-eus-competition-was-held-successfully/|title=The pilot edition of the kaixomundua.eus competition was held successfully|website=Domeinuak .eus|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tabakalera.eu/en/geomatics-and-spatial-intelligence|title=Geomatics and spatial intelligence|date=23 October 2017|website=tabakalera.eu|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Databases and Internet services ==\nThe UEU has created several databases and Internet services associated with new technologies to respond to training needs and to serve to the university community in Basque: \n\n*''Inguma'': database on the production of the Basque scientific community. Inguma is a source of information about everything that has been produced orally and in written form in Basque within the academic world since 1968 when the guidelines that led to the unification of the unified Basque language began to be set. In 2018, in total, it included cataloguing. There are both written documents (books, articles, prologues, reviews, translations, critical editions, research projects, doctoral theses) and oral documents summer         (conferences, courses, meetings, conferences, subjects).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.inguma.eus/ingumari-buruz/en|title=About Inguma. What is Inguma? Basque scientific-intellectual community|last=UEU|year=2000|website=inguma.eus|url-status=live|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n*''Artizarra'' social network for professionals and researchers.\n*''Buruxkak''. The digital library of the UEU, in 2018 it was offering the digital versions of 390 books from among the 419 published by this entity.\n*''Otarrea''. A compilation of works, reports, notes, and other types of university documents to be shared freely under a Creative Commons license. In 2018 it contained 941 documents distributed by fields in this way: Art and music (4), Humanities (112), Social sciences (333), Engineering and technology (393), Health sciences (19), Applied sciences (2) and Sciences (78).\n*''Tesiker'', PhD theses in Basque. The Tesiker database offers information and access to more than 450 theses that have been published in Basque. This web service is offered from the [[Basque Government]]'s website after having been collected by the UEU.\n*''Unibertsitatea.net'', meeting place and point of reference for anyone associated with or interested in the university, such as students, teaching staff, researchers, parents, members of the press, etc.university community portal. It publishes news about the Basque university community (including 140 interviews with young researchers, and 10 blogs (economy, Language processing, Art, Environment...).<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Iparrorratza'', orientation for university access. The Iparrorratza service offers a counselling service for young people entering university to help them choose their studies.\n\n== Building the community of young researchers ==\nSince 2012, the UEU has promoted the creation of a community of young researchers with the aim of promoting multidisciplinary knowledge and exchange. Three of its most relevant activities are the following:\n*''Ikergazte'' Congress (in Basque; Iker (research) gazte(young)) This congress has been held every two years since 2015. The number of participants was always greater than 200 and more than 120 articles were presented.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ueu.eus/ikergazte/en/|title=Third Conference for Basque young researchers. Ikergazte. Baiona 27\u201329 May 2019|last=UEU|date=27 May 2019|website=Ikergazte|url-status=live|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n*''Txiotesia'' Competition. With the same objective of promoting mutual knowledge, since 2012, this competition has been organized biennially. Participants describe their doctoral thesis work in just 6 tweets.\n* Web portal with interviews, The portal ''unibertsitatea.net'' has interviewed more than 120 young researchers.\n\n==Other universities operating in the Basque Country==\n*[[University of the Basque Country]]\n*[[University of Pau and the Adour region]]\n*[[University of Deusto]]\n*[[National University of Distance Education]]\n*[[University of Navarre]]\n*[[Universidad P\u00fablica de Navarra]]\n*[[Mondragon University]]\n*[[Musikene]]\n\n==Similar entities operating with other minority languages==\nThe following entities are similar to the UEU in that they work to promote the extensive use of a minority language at the university level:\n\n=== Catalan ===\n\n* The Catalan Summer University, ''Universitat Catalana d'Estiu'' (UCE) in Catalan language and officially. It is a summer university in Catalan language that takes place annually in the French town of [[Prades, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Orientales|Prades]]. It was founded in the summer of 1968, just after the events of May 1968.\n\n=== Irish ===\n\n*Fiontar is in Dublin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dcu.ie/fiontar_scoilnagaeilge/english/index.shtml|title=Fiontar Home \u2013 English Version {{!}} DCU|website=www.dcu.ie|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Acadamh na hOllscola\u00edochta Gaeilge|Acadamh na hOllscola\u00edochta]] is based in the [[West of Ireland]]. Its main campus is in the [[National University of Ireland, Galway|National University of Ireland]] in [[Galway]] City and it also has three other locations around the West of Ireland. They provide courses at different levels: degrees and postgraduate courses as well as diplomas and other short courses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nuigalway.ie/acadamh/eolasfuinn/|title=Eolas F\u00fainn \u2013 NUI Galway|website=nuigalway.ie|language=ga|url-status=live|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Col\u00e1iste na h\u00c9ireann]] (English: \"College of Ireland\") is a [[Tertiary education|third-level college]] in [[Dublin]], offering qualifications in the study of [[translation]] and the [[Irish language]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730203508/https://www.chg.gov.ie/ga/gaeltacht/the-irish-language/language-support-schemes/third-level-education-in-ireland/|title=Oideachas Tr\u00ed\u00fa Leibh\u00e9al in \u00c9irinn {{!}} An Roinn Cult\u00fair, Oidhreachta agus Gaeltachta|date=2019-07-30|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730203618/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/education/make-yourself-employable-with-a-postgrad-as-gaeilge-1.2560311|title=Make yourself employable with a postgrad as Gaeilge|date=2019-07-30|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Welsh ===\n\n* [[Coleg Cymraeg Cenedlaethol|Coleg Cymraeg ''Cenedlaethol'']] (in English: Welsh National College). It is known in both [[Welsh language|Welsh]] and English simply as ''Coleg''. It was established in 2011 by the [[Welsh Government]] to work with [[List of universities in Wales|universities in Wales]] to develop Welsh-language courses and resources for students; it also provides and advances Welsh medium courses, scholarship and research in Welsh universities. It works through branches in Welsh Universities to enable more opportunities to study for Welsh medium students in partnership with the universities.  Its aim is to increase the number of students who choose to study part or all of their course in Welsh.  It funds under- and post-graduate scholarships, sponsors Welsh medium lecturers and supports students who study in Welsh.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.colegcymraeg.ac.uk/cy/|title=Y Coleg Cymraeg Cenedlaethol|website=colegcymraeg.ac.uk|language=cy|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n*Y Gymdeithas Feddygol (Welsh language medical society) \u2013 supports the right to receive healthcare in Welsh and cooperates with any organisation to deliver it.  It encourages Welsh medium healthcare studies and gives opportunities to present their work in Welsh.  It gives opportunities for students and doctors to network in our annual conferences and the National Eisteddfod.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ygymdeithasfeddygol.cymru/|title=Cartref|website=Y Gymdeithas Feddygol|language=cy|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}{{Commons category}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[University of the Basque Country]]\n*[[Coleg Cymraeg Cenedlaethol|Coleg Cymraeg]]\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.ueu.eus/who-are-we Official website]\n*[http://www.inguma.eus/ingumari-buruz/en Inguma], database on the production of the Basque scientific community.\n*[http://www.buruxkak.eus/ Buruxkak], digital library of the Basque Summer University. More than 400 books published by the Basque Summer University.(in Basque)\n*[https://www.artizarra.eus/ Artizarra.eus], profesional social network. {{in lang|eu}}\n*[http://www.euskadi.eus/web01-apdoktes/eu/w10aTesDocWar/comunJSP/w10aPrincipal.do?idioma=eu Tesiker], database of PhD theses written in Basque {{in lang|eu|es}}\n*[https://www.unibertsitatea.net/blogak/ unibertsitatea.net], website of the university community in Basque (news, blogs...){{in lang|eu}}\n\n{{coord missing|France}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Spain]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in France]]\n[[Category:Basque culture]]\n", "name_user": "2.27.219.224", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Undid revision 949717427 byEagleash(talk))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basque_Summer_University"}
{"title_page": "Duncan Campbell (Unionist politician)", "text_new": "[[File:Duncan Frederick Campbell.jpg|thumb|Duncan Frederick Campbell in a photograph published in ''The Lancashire Fusiliers Annual 1916'' following his death in the First World War.]]\n'''Duncan Frederick Campbell''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|DSO}} (28 April 1876 [[Simcoe, Ontario|Simcoe]], Ontario, Canada \u2013 4 September 1916) was a [[Canada|Canadian]]-born British [[Unionist Party (Scotland)|Unionist]] MP for [[North Ayrshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Ayrshire]] who died in [[World War I]].\n\n==Life==\nCampbell was commissioned a [[second lieutenant]] in the [[Lancashire Fusiliers]] on 23 November 1898, followed by promotion to [[Lieutenant (British Army and Royal Marines)|lieutenant]] on 27 September 1899.<ref>{{London Gazette| issue=27165|page=1077| date=16 February 1900|}}</ref>\n\nHe served with the 2nd Battalion of his regiment in the [[Second Boer War]] 1899\u20131901, including as part of the [[Relief of Ladysmith|Ladysmith Relief Force]], and was slightly wounded at the engagement at Venters Spruit (20 January 1900), for which he was created a Companion of the [[Distinguished Service Order]] (DSO).<ref>\"Duncan Frederick Campbell, Lieutenant, Lancashire Fusiliers.  In recognition of services during the operations in South Africa\" (''London Gazette'', 19 April 1901)</ref> He was promoted [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]], 5 October 1901.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=27370 |date=1 November 1901 |page=7047}}</ref>\n\nCampbell fought [[Mid Lanarkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Lanarkshire]] for the Conservatives in [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]]. Campbell entered the House of Commons at a [[1911 North Ayrshire by-election|by-election]],  20 December 1911, defeating [[Andrew Anderson, Lord Anderson|Andrew Macbeth Anderson]] QC, who sought re-election on being appointed [[Solicitor General for Scotland]]. Anderson, in accordance with the constitutional arrangements of the day, was obliged to resign as an MP and fight a [[by-election]] on being appointed a [[Law Officers of the Crown|law officer of the Crown]]. The contest was dominated by the government's legislation on [[National Insurance Act 1911|National Insurance]] and the uncertainties this legislation would produce for individual electors, particularly those of small manufacturers and shopkeepers.  Although there was no Labour candidate, Anderson was thought to have lost some support among working-class voters because of his opposition to Labour candidates in other recent elections.<ref>''The Times'', 20 December 1911 p10</ref> After a tight contest, Campbell captured the seat by a majority of 271 votes.<ref>''The Times'', 22 December 1911 p6</ref>\n\n[[File:Crop showing D. F. Campbell's name on U of T Soldiers Tower memorial.jpg|thumb|left|Duncan Campbell's name on the [[Soldiers' Tower]] at the University of Toronto]]\nHe was wounded at the [[first battle of Ypres]] in November 1914 while serving with the [[Black Watch]]; he lost his left arm and was invalided for a year. As a lieutenant colonel in the [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment]], commanding 2nd/7th Bn, he was wounded by a mine on the Western Front and died of his wounds at [[Southwold]], Suffolk on 4 September 1916. He is buried in [[Kilmarnock]] Cemetery, Ayrshire.<ref>{{CWGC|id=663638|name=Campbell, Duncan Frederick|access-date=30 August 2016}}</ref> Campbell is commemorated on Panel 8 of the [[Parliamentary War Memorial]] in Westminster Hall, one of 22 MPs that died during World War I to be named on that memorial.<ref>{{cite web|title=Recording Angel memorial Panel 8|publisher=UK Parliament (www.parliament.uk)|website=Recording Angel memorial, Westminster Hall|url=http://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/building/cultural-collections/memorials/in-the-collection/world-war-i/wwi-angel-memorial/recording-angel-panel8/|access-date=31 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=List of names on the Recording Angel memorial, Westminster Hall|publisher=UK Parliament (www.parliament.uk)|website=Recording Angel memorial, Westminster Hall|url=http://www.parliament.uk/documents/War-Memorial-Lists/War-Memorial-Westminster-Hall-WW1.pdf|format=pdf|access-date=31 August 2016}}</ref> Campbell is one of 19 MPs who fell in the war who are commemorated by heraldic shields in the Commons Chamber.<ref>{{cite web|title=Campbell|publisher=UK Parliament (www.parliament.uk)|website=Heraldic shields to MPs, First World War|url=http://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/building/cultural-collections/memorials/in-the-collection/world-war-i/wars-heraldic-shields/campbell/|access-date=31 August 2016}}</ref> A further act of commemoration came with the unveiling in 1932 of a manuscript-style [[Illuminated manuscript|illuminated]] book of remembrance for the House of Commons, which includes a short biographical account of the life and death of Campbell.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=House of Commons War Memorial: Final Volumes Unveiled by The Speaker|day_of_week=Saturday |date=6 February 1932 |page_number=7|issue=46050}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor-last=Moss-Blundell|editor-first=Edward Whitaker|title=The House of Commons Book of Remembrance 1914\u20131918|publisher=E. Mathews & Marrot|year=1931}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{hansard-contribs | lieut-colonel-duncan-campbell | Duncan Frederick Campbell }}\n*[https://matthewkbarrett.com/2015/12/21/the-one-armed/#more-2357 The One-Armed] (Colonels of the Canadian Expeditionary Force)\n*[http://www.angloboerwar.com/name-search angloboerwar.com] (name database includes entry for Campbell)\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box  | title  = [[North Ayrshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Member of Parliament for North Ayrshire]]  | years  = 1911\u20131916  | before = [[Andrew Anderson, Lord Anderson|Andrew Anderson]]  | after  = [[Aylmer Hunter-Weston]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Campbell, Duncan Frederick}}\n[[Category:1876 births]]\n[[Category:1916 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Scottish constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:Duke of Wellington's Regiment officers]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:British military personnel killed in World War I]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Distinguished Service Order]]\n[[Category:Black Watch officers]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of the Second Boer War]]\n[[Category:Lancashire Fusiliers officers]]\n[[Category:Unionist Party (Scotland) MPs]]\n[[Category:People from Norfolk County, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Trinity College (Canada) alumni]]\n[[Category:Canadian emigrants to Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Duncan Frederick Campbell.jpg|thumb|Duncan Frederick Campbell in a photograph published in ''The Lancashire Fusiliers Annual 1916'' following his death in the First World War.]]\n'''Duncan Frederick Campbell''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|DSO}} (28 April 1876 [[Simcoe, Ontario|Simcoe]], Ontario, Canada \u2013 4 September 1916) was a [[Canada|Canadian]]-born British [[Unionist Party (Scotland)|Unionist]] MP for [[North Ayrshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Ayrshire]] who died in [[World War I]].\n\n==Life==\nCampbell was commissioned a [[second lieutenant]] in the [[Lancashire Fusiliers]] on 23 November 1898, followed by promotion to [[Lieutenant (British Army and Royal Marines)|lieutenant]] on 27 September 1899.<ref>{{London Gazette| issue=27165|page=1077| date=16 February 1900|}}</ref>\n\nHe served with the 2nd Battalion of his regiment in the [[Second Boer War]] 1899-1901, including as part of the [[Relief of Ladysmith|Ladysmith Relief Force]], and was slightly wounded at the engagement at Venters Spruit (20 January 1900), for which he was created a Companion of the [[Distinguished Service Order]] (DSO).<ref>\"Duncan Frederick Campbell, Lieutenant, Lancashire Fusiliers.  In recognition of services during the operations in South Africa\" (''London Gazette'', 19 April 1901)</ref> He was promoted [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]], 5 October 1901.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=27370 |date=1 November 1901 |page=7047}}</ref>\n\nCampbell fought [[Mid Lanarkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Lanarkshire]] for the Conservatives in [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]]. Campbell entered the House of Commons at a [[1911 North Ayrshire by-election|by-election]],  20 December 1911, defeating [[Andrew Anderson, Lord Anderson|Andrew Macbeth Anderson]] QC, who sought re-election on being appointed [[Solicitor General for Scotland]]. Anderson, in accordance with the constitutional arrangements of the day, was obliged to resign as an MP and fight a [[by-election]] on being appointed a [[Law Officers of the Crown|law officer of the Crown]]. The contest was dominated by the government\u2019s legislation on [[National Insurance Act 1911|National Insurance]] and the uncertainties this legislation would produce for individual electors, particularly those of small manufacturers and shopkeepers.  Although there was no Labour candidate, Anderson was thought to have lost some support among working-class voters because of his opposition to Labour candidates in other recent elections.<ref>''The Times'', 20 December 1911 p10</ref> After a tight contest, Campbell captured the seat by a majority of 271 votes.<ref>''The Times'', 22 December 1911 p6</ref>\n\n[[File:Crop showing D. F. Campbell's name on U of T Soldiers Tower memorial.jpg|thumb|left|Duncan Campbell's name on the [[Soldiers' Tower]] at the University of Toronto]]\nHe was wounded at the [[first battle of Ypres]] in November 1914 while serving with the [[Black Watch]]; he lost his left arm and was invalided for a year. As a lieutenant colonel in the [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment]], commanding 2nd/7th Bn, he was wounded by a mine on the Western Front and died of his wounds at [[Southwold]], Suffolk on 4 September 1916. He is buried in [[Kilmarnock]] Cemetery, Ayrshire.<ref>{{CWGC|id=663638|name=Campbell, Duncan Frederick|access-date=30 August 2016}}</ref> Campbell is commemorated on Panel 8 of the [[Parliamentary War Memorial]] in Westminster Hall, one of 22 MPs that died during World War I to be named on that memorial.<ref>{{cite web|title=Recording Angel memorial Panel 8|publisher=UK Parliament (www.parliament.uk)|website=Recording Angel memorial, Westminster Hall|url=http://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/building/cultural-collections/memorials/in-the-collection/world-war-i/wwi-angel-memorial/recording-angel-panel8/|access-date=31 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=List of names on the Recording Angel memorial, Westminster Hall|publisher=UK Parliament (www.parliament.uk)|website=Recording Angel memorial, Westminster Hall|url=http://www.parliament.uk/documents/War-Memorial-Lists/War-Memorial-Westminster-Hall-WW1.pdf|format=pdf|access-date=31 August 2016}}</ref> Campbell is one of 19 MPs who fell in the war who are commemorated by heraldic shields in the Commons Chamber.<ref>{{cite web|title=Campbell|publisher=UK Parliament (www.parliament.uk)|website=Heraldic shields to MPs, First World War|url=http://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/building/cultural-collections/memorials/in-the-collection/world-war-i/wars-heraldic-shields/campbell/|access-date=31 August 2016}}</ref> A further act of commemoration came with the unveiling in 1932 of a manuscript-style [[Illuminated manuscript|illuminated]] book of remembrance for the House of Commons, which includes a short biographical account of the life and death of Campbell.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=House of Commons War Memorial: Final Volumes Unveiled by The Speaker|day_of_week=Saturday |date=6 February 1932 |page_number=7|issue=46050}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor-last=Moss-Blundell|editor-first=Edward Whitaker|title=The House of Commons Book of Remembrance 1914\u20131918|publisher=E. Mathews & Marrot|year=1931}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{hansard-contribs | lieut-colonel-duncan-campbell | Duncan Frederick Campbell }}\n*[https://matthewkbarrett.com/2015/12/21/the-one-armed/#more-2357 The One-Armed] (Colonels of the Canadian Expeditionary Force)\n*[http://www.angloboerwar.com/name-search angloboerwar.com] (name database includes entry for Campbell)\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box  | title  = [[North Ayrshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Member of Parliament for North Ayrshire]]  | years  = 1911\u20131916  | before = [[Andrew Anderson, Lord Anderson|Andrew Anderson]]  | after  = [[Aylmer Hunter-Weston]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Campbell, Duncan Frederick}}\n[[Category:1876 births]]\n[[Category:1916 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Scottish constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:Duke of Wellington's Regiment officers]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:British military personnel killed in World War I]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Distinguished Service Order]]\n[[Category:Black Watch officers]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of the Second Boer War]]\n[[Category:Lancashire Fusiliers officers]]\n[[Category:Unionist Party (Scotland) MPs]]\n[[Category:People from Norfolk County, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Trinity College (Canada) alumni]]\n[[Category:Canadian emigrants to Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's, 1899-1901 \u2192 1899\u20131901", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Duncan_Campbell_(Unionist_politician)"}
{"title_page": "George B. Boomer", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name=George Boardman Boomer\n|birth_date= {{Birth date|1832|7|26}}\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|1863|5|24|1832|7|26}}\n|birth_place=[[Sutton, Massachusetts]]\n|death_place=[[Warren County, Mississippi]]\n|placeofburial= [[Worcester, Massachusetts]]\n|placeofburial_label= Place of burial\n|image=File:George B. Boomer.png\n|caption=George B. Boomer (1832-1863)\n|nickname=\n|allegiance= {{flagicon|USA}} [[United States|United States of America]]<br/>[[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch={{army|USA}} <br/>[[Union Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1861 - 1863\n|rank= [[File:Union Army brigadier general rank insignia.svg|30px]] [[Brigadier General]]\n|commands= [[26th Missouri Volunteer Infantry]]\n|unit=\n|battles=[[American Civil War]]\n|awards=\n|laterwork=\n}}\n'''George Boardman Boomer''' (July 26, 1832 \u2013 May 22, 1863) was a [[Union Army]] general who served as a brigade commander between February 12, 1863 and May 22, 1863 during the [[American Civil War]].<ref>Sifakis, Stewart, ''Who Was Who in the Civil War,'' p. 62. Facts on File Publications, New York, 1988. {{ISBN|0-8160-1055-2}}.</ref> His principal service was during the heavy engagement of his brigade on May 16, 1863 at the [[Battle of Champion Hill]] during the [[Siege of Vicksburg|Vicksburg]] campaign and in the second assault on Vicksburg on May 22, 1863.<ref>Smith, Timothy B., ''Champion Hill: Decisive Battle for Vicksburg,'' pp. 266-280. [[Savas Beatie]], New York, NY, 2004 (Paperback, 2006). {{ISBN|1-932714-19-7}}.</ref> Colonel Boomer was killed near the Railroad Redoubt on the second day of major assaults on the City of Vicksburg on May 22, 1863.<ref>Sifakis, 1988, p. 62; Smith, 2006, p. 401.</ref> He was commissioned Brigadier General around the time of his death.<ref name=\"auto\" >{{cite web|last=Dean|first=Benjamin Devor|title=Recollections of the 26th Missouri Infantry|url=http://freepages.military.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~the26thmo/history/historypage08.htm|accessdate=9 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBoomer was born in [[Sutton, Massachusetts]] on July 26, 1832. He attended [[Worcester Academy]] and graduated in 1847. Because of poor eyesight, Boomer did not go on to college. Instead, he joined his brother-in-law in building bridges across the Mississippi River.<ref>Jackson, Robert Wendell. ''Rails across the Mississippi: a history of the St. Louis bridge''. Urbana, IL: University of Illinois Press, 2001. {{ISBN|978-0-252-02680-5}}.</ref>\n\nAt the outbreak of the Civil War, he raised a company for the Union Army which became part of the 26th Missouri Volunteer Infantry Regiment<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Bench and Bar of St. Louis, Kansas City, Jefferson City, and Other Missouri Cities: Biographical Sketches|year=2010|publisher=[[Nabu Press]]|isbn=978-1-145-52442-2|editor=American Biographical Publishing Company|page=27}}</ref> and by 1863 was promoted to colonel. He distinguished himself at [[Siege of Vicksburg|Vicksburg]] as brigade commander under [[Major General (United States)|Major General]] [[James B. McPherson]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Scherneckau|first=August|title=Marching With the First Nebraska: A Civil War Diary|year=2007|publisher=[[University of Oklahoma Press]]|isbn=978-0-8061-3808-4|page=165}}</ref>\n\n==Battle of Champion Hill==\nBoomer and his men distinguished themselves in the Battle of Champion Hill on May 16, 1863. Below is the description of the battle by Benjamin Devor Dean, Captain, at the time, of the 26th Missouri:\n\n\"The 26th went into this engagement under very trying circumstances. General Hovey\u2019s Division was being hard pressed, and falling back, the Third Brigade, Col. Boomer, commanding, was ordered up on the double-quick. The ground over which the 26th Missouri passed, was very much obstructed, and in consequence some of the companies had to break the line of battle and move by the flank under the shells of the enemy. On reaching the line of battle, notwithstanding our fatigue, the 10th Iowa and 93rd Illinois immediately engaged the enemy; the 5th Iowa and 26th Missouri lying down behind them waiting their turn which soon came. Colonel Boomer, our gallant brigade commander, seeing the enemy approaching on our right flank, ordered the 26th Missouri to meet them, which it did on the double quick by \"about face,\" \"half wheel\" and forward movement, getting possession of a deep ravine which the enemy was trying to secure. \nThe position gained by the above movement was a strong one, and enabled us to stop the enemy who outnumbered the 26th Missouri, which finally drove the Confederates from before it, after firing forty rounds of ammunition. Being nearly surrounded by the enemy, we changed our position under heavy fire, but the position was so strong that the loss was slight considering the hot engagement.  We charged the rebels, drove them back and captured a number of prisoners. On falling back to Acting General Boomer\u2019s position, he earnestly complimented the 26th Missouri for their gallant conduct on the field.\"<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\n==Death==\n[[File:The base of the Boomer Column.png|thumb|The base of the Boomer Column, Rural Cemetery, Worcester, MA]]Six days after the heroic actions at Champion Hill, Colonel Boomer was killed in the second assault on Vicksburg on May 22, 1863.<ref>Sifakis, 1988, p. 62; Smith, 2006, p. 401. The other source that was cited is{{Cite book|author=Indiana-Vicksburg Military Park Commission|title=Indiana at Vicksburg|year=2009|publisher=University of Michigan Library|page=57}}</ref> \n[[File:Boomer Column.png|thumb|Boomer Column Rural Cemetery Worcester, MA]]According to Benjamin Devor Dean, on May 22 Colonel Boomer led his men on a brave charge upon one of the forts that made up Vicksburg's defenses. Colonel Boomer had advised against storming the fort, warning his superiors that it had not yet been \"silenced\" of its arms. But his superiors did not listen to his advice, so Colonel Boomer and his men charged the fort gallantly.  As Boomer predicted, the fort had not been silenced and immediately he and his men came under heavy fire - \"an incessant shower of shot, shell and rifle balls.\" Colonel Boomer and his men were momentarily forced to take cover.  Soon afterwards, Colonel Boomer courageously decided to push on - he personally \"rose up, and had shouted \"Attention!\" as if to resume the charge, when a rifle ball struck him in the head, killing him instantly.\" Colonel Boomer, who was already an Acting General at the time, had just been commissioned Brigadier General - but he himself would never know this. Reportedly, the commission as Brigadier General arrived in camp shortly after his death.<ref name=\"auto\"/>  \nHis body was returned to [[Worcester, Massachusetts]] and thousands attended his funeral. He was buried in [[Rural Cemetery (Worcester, Massachusetts)|Rural Cemetery]] in Worcester<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/6101530|title=Grave Brig.Gen. George B. Boomer}}</ref>\nand the monument honoring him is a thirty-foot column with a large eagle at the top.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rice|first=Franklin Pierce|title=The Worcester Book: A Diary of Noteworthy Events|year=2008|publisher=[[BiblioLife]]|isbn=978-0-559-59002-3|page=73}}</ref> His bravery was written about at the time.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Ballard|first=Michael B.|title=Vicksburg: The Campaign That Opened the Mississippi (Civil War America)|year=2003|publisher=[[University of North Carolina Press]]|isbn=978-0-8078-2893-9|page=424|quote=In 1864, ''Elegy'' was published as a memorial to Union \"general\" George Boomer, who had been killed during the siege, and ''Grant's the Man'' by C.L. Abdill praised the \"general's\" heroics.}}</ref>\n\nA memoir of Colonel Boomer's life was published by his sister, Mary Amelia Boomer Stone, in 1864.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Stone|first=Mary Amelia Boomer|title=Memoir of George Boardman Boomer|year=2010|publisher=[[General Books LLC]]|isbn=978-1-154-78181-6|pages=98}}</ref>\n\n{{Portal|American Civil War}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{Cite book|title=The Bench and Bar of St. Louis, Kansas City, Jefferson City, and Other Missouri Cities: Biographical Sketches|year=2010|publisher=[[Nabu Press]]|isbn=978-1-145-52442-2|editor=American Biographical Publishing Company}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Ballard|first=Michael B.|title=Vicksburg: The Campaign That Opened the Mississippi (Civil War America)|year=2003|publisher=[[University of North Carolina Press]]|isbn=978-0-8078-2893-9}}\n*{{Cite journal|journal=Civil War Regiments: A Journal of the American Civil War|year=1993|volume=3|issue=3|publisher=Savas Publishing Company}}\n*Eicher, John H., and Eicher, David J., ''Civil War High Commands,'' [[Stanford University Press]], 2001, {{ISBN|0-8047-3641-3}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Foote|first=Shelby|title=The Civil War: a narrative, Volume 2|year=1974|publisher=[[Random House]]|page=372}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Grimsley|first=Mark|title=Union Must Stand: Civil War Diaries John Quincy Adams Campbell (Voices Of The Civil War)|year=2000|publisher=[[Univ Tennessee Press]]|isbn=978-1-57233-069-6}}\n*Hunt, Roger D. and Brown, Jack R., ''Brevet Brigadier Generals in Blue.'' Olde Soldier Books, Inc., Gaithersburg, MD, 1990. {{ISBN|1-56013-002-4}}.\n*Jackson, Robert Wendell. ''Rails across the Mississippi: a history of the St. Louis bridge''. Urbana, IL: University of Illinois Press, 2001. {{ISBN|978-0-252-02680-5}}.\n*{{Cite book|last=Rice|first=Franklin Pierce|title=The Worcester Book: A Diary of Noteworthy Events|year=2008|publisher=[[BiblioLife]]|isbn=978-0-559-59002-3|page=73}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Scherneckau|first=August|title=Marching With the First Nebraska: A Civil War Diary|year=2007|publisher=[[University of Oklahoma Press]]|isbn=978-0-8061-3808-4|page=165}}\n*Sifakis, Stewart, ''Who Was Who in the Civil War,'' p.&nbsp;62. Facts on File Publications, New York, 1988. {{ISBN|0-8160-1055-2}}\n*Smith, Timothy B., ''Champion Hill: Decisive Battle for Vicksburg,'' pp.&nbsp;266\u2013280. [[Savas Beatie]], New York, NY, 2004 (Paperback, 2006). {{ISBN|1-932714-19-7}}.\n*{{Cite book|last=Stone|first=Mary Amelia Boomer|title=Memoir of George Boardman Boomer|year=2010|publisher=[[General Books LLC]]|isbn=978-1-154-78181-6|pages=98}}\n*United States War Department, The Military Secretary's Office, ''Memorandum Relative to the General Officers in the Armies of the '''United States''' During the Civil War, 1861&ndash;1865,'' (Compiled from Official Records, almost certainly by General Marcus Wright.) 1906. https://archive.org/details/memorandumrelati05unit, retrieved August 5, 2010.\n*Warner, Ezra J., ''Generals in Blue.'' [[Louisiana State University Press]], Baton Rouge, 1964. {{ISBN|0-8071-0822-7}}\n*{{Cite journal|author=Worcester Historical Society|title=Proceedings of the Worcester Society of Antiquity|journal=Proceedings of the Worcester Society of Antiquity|volume=9|accessdate=|page=160}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boomer, George B.}}\n[[Category:1832 births]]\n[[Category:1863 deaths]]\n[[Category:Union Army generals]]\n[[Category:Union military personnel killed in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:People of Massachusetts in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:People from Sutton, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Burials at Rural Cemetery (Worcester, Massachusetts)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name=George Boardman Boomer\n|birth_date= {{Birth date|1832|7|26}}\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|1863|5|24|1832|7|26}}\n|birth_place=[[Sutton, Massachusetts]]\n|death_place=[[Warren County, Mississippi]]\n|placeofburial= [[Worcester, Massachusetts]]\n|placeofburial_label= Place of burial\n|image=File:George B. Boomer.png\n|caption=George B. Boomer (1832-1863)\n|nickname=\n|allegiance= {{flagicon|USA}} [[United States|United States of America]]<br/>[[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch={{army|USA}} <br/>[[Union Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1861 - 1863\n|rank= [[File:Union Army brigadier general rank insignia.svg|30px]] [[Brigadier General]]\n|commands= [[26th Missouri Volunteer Infantry]]\n|unit=\n|battles=[[American Civil War]]\n|awards=\n|laterwork=\n}}\n'''George Boardman Boomer''' (July 26, 1832 \u2013 May 22, 1863) was a [[Union Army]] general who served as a brigade commander between February 12, 1863 and May 22, 1863 during the [[American Civil War]].<ref>Sifakis, Stewart, ''Who Was Who in the Civil War,'' p. 62. Facts on File Publications, New York, 1988. {{ISBN|0-8160-1055-2}}.</ref> His principal service was during the heavy engagement of his brigade on May 16, 1863 at the [[Battle of Champion Hill]] during the [[Siege of Vicksburg|Vicksburg]] campaign and in the second assault on Vicksburg on May 22, 1863.<ref>Smith, Timothy B., ''Champion Hill: Decisive Battle for Vicksburg,'' pp. 266-280. [[Savas Beatie]], New York, NY, 2004 (Paperback, 2006). {{ISBN|1-932714-19-7}}.</ref> Colonel Boomer was killed near the Railroad Redoubt on the second day of major assaults on the City of Vicksburg on May 22, 1863.<ref>Sifakis, 1988, p. 62; Smith, 2006, p. 401.</ref> He was commissioned Brigadier General around the time of his death.<ref name=\"auto\" >{{cite web|last=Dean|first=Benjamin Devor|title=Recollections of the 26th Missouri Infantry|url=http://freepages.military.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~the26thmo/history/historypage08.htm|accessdate=9 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBoomer was born in [[Sutton, Massachusetts]] on July 26, 1832. He attended [[Worcester Academy]] and graduated in 1847. Because of poor eyesight, Boomer did not go on to college. Instead, he joined his brother-in-law in building bridges across the Mississippi River.<ref>Jackson, Robert Wendell. ''Rails across the Mississippi: a history of the St. Louis bridge''. Urbana, IL: University of Illinois Press, 2001. {{ISBN|978-0-252-02680-5}}.</ref>\n\nAt the outbreak of the Civil War, he raised a company for the Union Army which became part of the 26th Missouri Volunteer Infantry Regiment<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Bench and Bar of St. Louis, Kansas City, Jefferson City, and Other Missouri Cities: Biographical Sketches|year=2010|publisher=[[Nabu Press]]|isbn=978-1-145-52442-2|editor=American Biographical Publishing Company|page=27}}</ref> and by 1863 was promoted to colonel. He distinguished himself at [[Siege of Vicksburg|Vicksburg]] as brigade commander under [[Major General (United States)|Major General]] [[James B. McPherson]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Scherneckau|first=August|title=Marching With the First Nebraska: A Civil War Diary|year=2007|publisher=[[University of Oklahoma Press]]|isbn=978-0-8061-3808-4|page=165}}</ref>\n\n==Battle of Champion Hill==\nBoomer and his men distinguished themselves in the Battle of Champion Hill on May 16, 1863. Below is the description of the battle by Benjamin Devor Dean, the second commanding colonel of Boomer's 26th Missouri:\n\n\"The 26th went into this engagement under very trying circumstances. General Hovey\u2019s Division was being hard pressed, and falling back, the Third Brigade, Col. Boomer, commanding, was ordered up on the double-quick. The ground over which the 26th Missouri passed, was very much obstructed, and in consequence some of the companies had to break the line of battle and move by the flank under the shells of the enemy. On reaching the line of battle, notwithstanding our fatigue, the 10th Iowa and 93rd Illinois immediately engaged the enemy; the 5th Iowa and 26th Missouri lying down behind them waiting their turn which soon came. Colonel Boomer, our gallant brigade commander, seeing the enemy approaching on our right flank, ordered the 26th Missouri to meet them, which it did on the double quick by \"about face,\" \"half wheel\" and forward movement, getting possession of a deep ravine which the enemy was trying to secure. \nThe position gained by the above movement was a strong one, and enabled us to stop the enemy who outnumbered the 26th Missouri, which finally drove the Confederates from before it, after firing forty rounds of ammunition. Being nearly surrounded by the enemy, we changed our position under heavy fire, but the position was so strong that the loss was slight considering the hot engagement.  We charged the rebels, drove them back and captured a number of prisoners. On falling back to Acting General Boomer\u2019s position, he earnestly complimented the 26th Missouri for their gallant conduct on the field.\"<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\n==Death==\n[[File:The base of the Boomer Column.png|thumb|The base of the Boomer Column, Rural Cemetery, Worcester, MA]]Six days after the heroic actions at Champion Hill, Colonel Boomer was killed in the second assault on Vicksburg on May 22, 1863.<ref>Sifakis, 1988, p. 62; Smith, 2006, p. 401. The other source that was cited is{{Cite book|author=Indiana-Vicksburg Military Park Commission|title=Indiana at Vicksburg|year=2009|publisher=University of Michigan Library|page=57}}</ref> \n[[File:Boomer Column.png|thumb|Boomer Column Rural Cemetery Worcester, MA]]According to Benjamin Devor Dean, on May 22 Colonel Boomer led his men on a brave charge upon one of the forts that made up Vicksburg's defenses. Colonel Boomer had advised against storming the fort, warning his superiors that it had not yet been \"silenced\" of its arms. But his superiors did not listen to his advice, so Colonel Boomer and his men charged the fort gallantly.  As Boomer predicted, the fort had not been silenced and immediately he and his men came under heavy fire - \"an incessant shower of shot, shell and rifle balls.\" Colonel Boomer and his men were momentarily forced to take cover.  Soon afterwards, Colonel Boomer courageously decided to push on - he personally \"rose up, and had shouted \"Attention!\" as if to resume the charge, when a rifle ball struck him in the head, killing him instantly.\" Colonel Boomer, who was already an Acting General at the time, had just been commissioned Brigadier General - but he himself would never know this. Reportedly, the commission as Brigadier General arrived in camp shortly after his death.<ref name=\"auto\"/>  \nHis body was returned to [[Worcester, Massachusetts]] and thousands attended his funeral. He was buried in [[Rural Cemetery (Worcester, Massachusetts)|Rural Cemetery]] in Worcester<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/6101530|title=Grave Brig.Gen. George B. Boomer}}</ref>\nand the monument honoring him is a thirty-foot column with a large eagle at the top.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rice|first=Franklin Pierce|title=The Worcester Book: A Diary of Noteworthy Events|year=2008|publisher=[[BiblioLife]]|isbn=978-0-559-59002-3|page=73}}</ref> His bravery was written about at the time.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Ballard|first=Michael B.|title=Vicksburg: The Campaign That Opened the Mississippi (Civil War America)|year=2003|publisher=[[University of North Carolina Press]]|isbn=978-0-8078-2893-9|page=424|quote=In 1864, ''Elegy'' was published as a memorial to Union \"general\" George Boomer, who had been killed during the siege, and ''Grant's the Man'' by C.L. Abdill praised the \"general's\" heroics.}}</ref>\n\nA memoir of Colonel Boomer's life was published by his sister, Mary Amelia Boomer Stone, in 1864.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Stone|first=Mary Amelia Boomer|title=Memoir of George Boardman Boomer|year=2010|publisher=[[General Books LLC]]|isbn=978-1-154-78181-6|pages=98}}</ref>\n\n{{Portal|American Civil War}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{Cite book|title=The Bench and Bar of St. Louis, Kansas City, Jefferson City, and Other Missouri Cities: Biographical Sketches|year=2010|publisher=[[Nabu Press]]|isbn=978-1-145-52442-2|editor=American Biographical Publishing Company}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Ballard|first=Michael B.|title=Vicksburg: The Campaign That Opened the Mississippi (Civil War America)|year=2003|publisher=[[University of North Carolina Press]]|isbn=978-0-8078-2893-9}}\n*{{Cite journal|journal=Civil War Regiments: A Journal of the American Civil War|year=1993|volume=3|issue=3|publisher=Savas Publishing Company}}\n*Eicher, John H., and Eicher, David J., ''Civil War High Commands,'' [[Stanford University Press]], 2001, {{ISBN|0-8047-3641-3}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Foote|first=Shelby|title=The Civil War: a narrative, Volume 2|year=1974|publisher=[[Random House]]|page=372}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Grimsley|first=Mark|title=Union Must Stand: Civil War Diaries John Quincy Adams Campbell (Voices Of The Civil War)|year=2000|publisher=[[Univ Tennessee Press]]|isbn=978-1-57233-069-6}}\n*Hunt, Roger D. and Brown, Jack R., ''Brevet Brigadier Generals in Blue.'' Olde Soldier Books, Inc., Gaithersburg, MD, 1990. {{ISBN|1-56013-002-4}}.\n*Jackson, Robert Wendell. ''Rails across the Mississippi: a history of the St. Louis bridge''. Urbana, IL: University of Illinois Press, 2001. {{ISBN|978-0-252-02680-5}}.\n*{{Cite book|last=Rice|first=Franklin Pierce|title=The Worcester Book: A Diary of Noteworthy Events|year=2008|publisher=[[BiblioLife]]|isbn=978-0-559-59002-3|page=73}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Scherneckau|first=August|title=Marching With the First Nebraska: A Civil War Diary|year=2007|publisher=[[University of Oklahoma Press]]|isbn=978-0-8061-3808-4|page=165}}\n*Sifakis, Stewart, ''Who Was Who in the Civil War,'' p.&nbsp;62. Facts on File Publications, New York, 1988. {{ISBN|0-8160-1055-2}}\n*Smith, Timothy B., ''Champion Hill: Decisive Battle for Vicksburg,'' pp.&nbsp;266\u2013280. [[Savas Beatie]], New York, NY, 2004 (Paperback, 2006). {{ISBN|1-932714-19-7}}.\n*{{Cite book|last=Stone|first=Mary Amelia Boomer|title=Memoir of George Boardman Boomer|year=2010|publisher=[[General Books LLC]]|isbn=978-1-154-78181-6|pages=98}}\n*United States War Department, The Military Secretary's Office, ''Memorandum Relative to the General Officers in the Armies of the '''United States''' During the Civil War, 1861&ndash;1865,'' (Compiled from Official Records, almost certainly by General Marcus Wright.) 1906. https://archive.org/details/memorandumrelati05unit, retrieved August 5, 2010.\n*Warner, Ezra J., ''Generals in Blue.'' [[Louisiana State University Press]], Baton Rouge, 1964. {{ISBN|0-8071-0822-7}}\n*{{Cite journal|author=Worcester Historical Society|title=Proceedings of the Worcester Society of Antiquity|journal=Proceedings of the Worcester Society of Antiquity|volume=9|accessdate=|page=160}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boomer, George B.}}\n[[Category:1832 births]]\n[[Category:1863 deaths]]\n[[Category:Union Army generals]]\n[[Category:Union military personnel killed in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:People of Massachusetts in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:People from Sutton, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Burials at Rural Cemetery (Worcester, Massachusetts)]]\n", "name_user": "Wilto01", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBattle of Champion Hill:Dean was a captain at the time of the battle of Champion Hill.  See the order of battle for the Vicksburg campaign.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_B._Boomer"}
{"title_page": "Music (Madonna album)", "text_new": "{{short description|2000 studio album by Madonna}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Music\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]\n| cover        = Music Madonna.png\n| alt          = \n| released     = September 18, 2000\n| recorded     = 1999\u20132000\n| studio       = [[Sarm East Studios|Sarm East]] and [[Sarm West Studios|West]]<br/>{{small|(London)}}<br/>Guerilla Beach Studios<br/> {{small|(Los Angeles)}}<br/>[[The Hit Factory]]<br/>{{small|(New York City)}}\n| genre        = *[[Pop music|Pop]]\n*[[electronica]]\n*[[dance-pop]]\n| length       = 44:40\n| label        = *[[Maverick (company)|Maverick]]\n*[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n| producer     = *Madonna\n*[[Mirwais Ahmadza\u00ef]]\n*[[William Orbit]]\n*[[Guy Sigsworth]]\n*[[Spike Stent|Mark \"Spike\" Stent]]\n*[[Talvin Singh]]\n| prev_title   = [[Ray of Light]]\n| prev_year    = 1998\n| next_title   = [[GHV2]]\n| next_year    = 2001\n| misc         = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = Madonna studio album\n | type       = studio\n | prev_title = Ray of Light\n | prev_year  = 1998\n | title      = Music\n | year       = 2000\n | next_title = [[American Life]]\n | next_year  = 2003\n}}\n\n{{Singles\n | name        = Music\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Music (Madonna song)|Music]]\n | single1date = August 21, 2000\n | single2     = [[Don't Tell Me (Madonna song)|Don't Tell Me]]\n | single2date = November 14, 2000\n | single3     = [[What It Feels Like for a Girl]]\n | single3date = April 16, 2001\n}}\n}}\n'''''Music''''' is the eighth studio album by American singer [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], released on September 18, 2000 by [[Maverick (company)|Maverick]] and [[Warner Bros. Records]]. Following the success of her previous album ''[[Ray of Light]]'' (1998), she intended to embark on a tour. However, her record company encouraged her to return to the studio and record new music before going on the road. Her collaboration with producers [[Mirwais Ahmadza\u00ef]] and [[William Orbit]] resulted in a more experimental direction for the album. ''Music'' has an overall [[dance-pop]] and [[electronica]] vibe, with influences from [[Rock music|rock]], [[Country music|country]] and [[Folk music|folk]]. The album was mostly recorded at Sarm West and East Studios in London, England. Elaborating a [[Rural area|country]] theme for the album, Madonna reinvented her image as a [[cowgirl]].\n\n''Music'' was generally acclaimed by most critics and earned five [[Grammy Award]] nominations, ultimately winning one for [[Best Recording Package]] given to art director Kevin Reagan. In 2003, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ranked it number 452 on their list of [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time]]. The record was also a commercial success, debuting at number one in over 23 countries across the world and selling four million copies in its first ten days of release. In the United States, ''Music'' debuted at number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] with first week sales of 420,000 units, making it her first album to top the chart in more than a decade since ''[[Like a Prayer (album)|Like a Prayer]]'' (1989). It was certified [[RIAA certification|triple platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) for three million units shipped in the United States and has sold over 15 million copies worldwide.\n\nThe album was promoted with her concerts at [[Brixton Academy]] and [[Roseland Ballroom]], as well as several television performances such as the [[2000 MTV Europe Music Awards]] and the [[43rd Grammy Awards]]. It was also supported by the [[Drowned World Tour]], which grossed over US$75 million, making it the highest-grossing tour by a solo act of 2001 (the fourth overall). Three singles were released from the album. The lead single, \"[[Music (Madonna song)|Music]]\", topped the record charts in 25 countries worldwide and became Madonna's 12th and last number-one hit on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. It was followed with another Hot 100 top-five hit \"[[Don't Tell Me (Madonna song)|Don't Tell Me]]\" and \"[[What It Feels Like for a Girl]]\" which attained the top-ten position in several countries worldwide. \"[[Impressive Instant]]\" was released as promotional single, peaking at number one on the [[Hot Dance Club Play]] chart.\n\n== Background ==\nAfter the critical and commercial success of her album ''[[Ray of Light]]'' (1998), Madonna intended to embark on a new concert tour in September 1999, but due to the delay of her film ''[[The Next Best Thing]]'', which she started filming in April 1999, the tour was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.mtv.com/news/512811/film-delay-blamed-for-madonna-tour-cancellation/| title=Film Delay Blamed For Madonna Tour Cancellation| last=Kaufman| first=Gil| publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=March 15, 1999|accessdate=December 19, 2017}}</ref> In June 1999, Madonna released a song recorded for the film ''[[Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me]]'', called \"[[Beautiful Stranger]]\". It peaked number nineteen on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and received a [[Grammy]] at the [[42nd Grammy Awards]] for \"[[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for Visual Media|Best Song Written for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media]]\".<ref name=\"grammy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/GRAMMY_Awards/Winners/Results.aspx?title=&winner=Madonna&year=0&genreID=0&hp=1 |title=Grammy Award Winners \u2013 Madonna |publisher=[[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]] |accessdate=May 27, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090111041645/http://www.grammy.com/GRAMMY_Awards/Winners/Results.aspx?title=&winner=Madonna&year=0&genreID=0&hp=1 |archivedate=January 11, 2009 }}</ref> In March 2000, Madonna released a cover version of [[Don McLean]]'s \"[[American Pie (song)#Madonna version|American Pie]]\" (1971) as part of the soundtrack of the film ''The Next Best Thing''. The song received mixed reviews, and was a success in European charts. Although not released commercially in the United States, it reached number 29 on the Hot 100 chart due to strong radio airplay.<ref>{{cite journal| last=Taylor| first=Chuck| date=February 12, 2000| title=Spotlight: Madonna \"American Pie\"| journal=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|  url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4Q0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA22&dq=Madonna+Spotlight&cd=10#v=onepage&q=Madonna%20Spotlight&f=false| volume=112| issue=7| page=22| issn=0006-2510| accessdate=July 25, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/madonna/2653 |title=NME Track Reviews \u2013 American Pie |work=[[NME]] |date=February 26, 2000 |accessdate=July 25, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Madonna&titel=American+Pie&cat=s |title=Madonna \u2013 American Pie |publisher=Lescharts. Hung Medien |accessdate=July 25, 2013}}</ref><ref>[{{BillboardURLbyName|artist=madonna|chart=all}} Billboard chart peaks] Billboard.com. Retrieved June 22, 2009.</ref>\n\nBy 2000, she became pregnant with her son Rocco, from her relationship with director [[Guy Ritchie]].<ref name=mirror>{{cite news| title=Guy Ritchie turns to Sting's wife Trudie Styler to save his marriage to Madonna| url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/guy-ritchie-turns-to-stings-wife-315871| date=June 30, 2008| work=[[Daily Mirror]]| accessdate=September 15, 2014}}</ref> Wanting to distract herself from the media frenzy surrounding this news, Madonna concentrated on the development of her eighth studio album, entitled ''Music''. Buoyed by the commercial success of her previous album, she was keen on getting back to the studio to record new music. Madonna was well disposed towards [[William Orbit]], producer of ''Ray of Light'', but by 2000, his production and sound had become ubiquitous. Also, the music scene was being dominated by a younger generation of singers like [[Britney Spears]] and [[Christina Aguilera]], prompting Madonna to look for a distinctive sound within this market.<ref name=\"obr1\">{{harvnb|O'Brien|2008|p=338}}</ref> She was then introduced to French DJ and producer [[Mirwais Ahmadza\u00ef]]. Madonna instantly liked his pitch-shifting, pulverizing rhythms and his utilization of [[Acid techno|acid bass]] in his songs. Ahmadza\u00ef always preferred taking musical risks and hence he wanted the collaborations with Madonna to get out the best from the singer.<ref name=\"obr2\">{{harvnb|O'Brien|2008|p=339}}</ref> Before the album was released, Madonna recorded a statement to her fans, stating about the album and Ahmadza\u00ef:\n\n<blockquote>\n\"Hey Mr. DJ, put a record on... Hi, it's Madonna. You've probably been hearing about my new record, ''Music'', for a while. Well, I just wanted to make sure you knew that the single is gonna drop very soon. I worked on it with a French guy named Mirwais, and he is the shit. The album will be released worldwide on September 19, and I hope you like my music.\"<ref name=\"baby\">{{cite journal| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/madonna-gives-birth-to-a-baby-boy-20000814| title=Madonna Gives Birth to a Baby Boy| work=[[Rolling Stone]]| date=August 14, 2000| accessdate=January 23, 2012}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n== Development ==\nMadonna approached British house [[DJ Sasha]] to work on her album, and began writing new material together.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www2.dotmusic.com/artists/Madonna/news/December1999/news12501.asp |title=Exclusive: DJ Sasha Working with Madonna |date=December 21, 1999 |accessdate=October 6, 2016 |publisher=[[Dotmusic]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000521163757/http://www2.dotmusic.com/artists/Madonna/news/December1999/news12501.asp |archivedate=May 21, 2000 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Madonna also planned to continue her work with Orbit for the album. He commented that the material was \"quite a little edgier than ''Ray of Light'', elaborating that \"It's almost like we started off with a lot of slow ballad songs and she's started to kind of chuck 'em out in favor of more edgy tracks. The album is getting more kind of fast, very European sounding, very English and French sounding, naturally, 'cause everybody working on it apart from her is English or French. Pretty exciting, actually. It's like a follow-up for Ray Of Light without stopping still. It's perfect\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Weiss |first=Neal |url=http://launch.yahoo.com/read/news.asp?contentID=161658 |title=Madonna Preparing More 'Rays Of Light' |date=January 31, 2000 |accessdate=October 6, 2016 |publisher=[[Launch.com]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020211090643/http://launch.yahoo.com/read/news.asp?contentID=161658 |archivedate=February 11, 2002 |url-status=dead }}</ref> But after some recording sessions, she felt she needed a different sound for her project, scrapping most of the material and began looking for new producers to work with.<ref>{{harvnb|O'Brien|2009|p=239}}</ref> Recording sessions began in January 2000 at Sarm West and East Studios in London, England.<ref name=\"obr2\"/>\n\nIt was then that French producer [[Mirwais Ahmadza\u00ef]] was introduced by Madonna's manager [[Guy Oseary]]. In an interview with [[CNN]], she stated, \"Guy Oseary, my partner at Maverick [Records], was given a demo by a French artist called Mirwais. [He] slipped it to me and said, 'What do you think [of him] as an artist to sign at Maverick?' [...] I just said 'Oh my God, this is what I want.' I just flipped over it and said, 'Please find out if he wants to work with me.'\"<ref name=\"cnn\"/> Ahmadza\u00ef spoke little English, and Madonna commented: \"The first couple of days we were recording, I wanted to rip my hair out. [...] It didn't seem like there was any way for us to communicate. His manager had to come in and translate everything at first.\"<ref name=\"billaugust\">{{cite journal| last=Walter| first=Barry| date=August 5, 2000| title=Madonna Offers Upbeat 'Music' on Maverick| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mBAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA1| journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]| issn=0006-2510| accessdate=May 14, 2012| issue=32| volume=112| page=98}}</ref>\n\nShe also commented about working with Ahmadza\u00ef and the other producers of the album: \"I love to work with the weirdos that no one knows about\u2014the people who have raw talent and who are making music unlike anyone else out there. ''Music'' is the future of sound.\"<ref name=\"bronmusic\">{{harvnb|Bronson|2002|p=989}}</ref> Madonna had later proclaimed Ahmadza\u00ef to be a musical \"genius\".<ref name=\"billaugust\"/> In an interview with [[MTV]]'s ''[[Total Request Live]]'', she said Ahmadza\u00ef was \"really influenced by 1970s funk and R&B\" and said that the album was \"more electronic than her [[Ray of Light|last record]], but it is edgier and a bit funkier\".<ref>{{cite web| last=Mancini| first=Robert| url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431551/update-madonna-promises-funkier-edgier-new-album-talks-club-dates.jhtml| title=UPDATE: Madonna Promises \"Funkier, Edgier\" New Album, Talks Club Dates| work=MTV News| date=August 3, 2000| accessdate=May 14, 2012}}</ref> Talking about the inspiration behind ''Music'', Madonna said the album was \"To join the coldness or the remoteness of living in the machine age in the world of high technology with warmth and compassion and a sense of humor. [...] ''Music'' is supposed to be a reflection of what's going on in society, and as far as I'm concerned, we've become too complacent.\"<ref name=\"lib\">{{cite web| url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Madonna%27s+Exclusive+%27Global+Listening+Party%27+on+Spinner.com+and+AOL%27s...-a065310230| title=Madonna's Exclusive 'Global Listening Party' on Spinner.com and AOL's Online Chat Attracts Tens of Thousands of Fans...and Here's What She Had to Say...| work=[[Business Wire]]| date=September 19, 2000| publisher=The Free Library| accessdate=May 14, 2012}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[The Face (magazine)|The Face]]'', Madonna was questioned about her mood while developing the album. She commented,\n<blockquote>\n\"To tell you the truth, I didn't know what the mood was. I feel like an animal that's, like, ready to be sprung from a cage. I've been living a pretty low-key domestic existence and I miss things. Like, I miss performing, and dancing, and being on the road, that kind of energy. So part of the record is about that. And then the other part is about love. So there's the frivolous side of my life and then there's the \u2013hopefully\u2013 non-frivolous side of my life. I usually make a record that's one or the other, and I feel I did both on this one\".<ref name=\"face\"/>\n</blockquote>\n\n== Music structure and lyrics ==\n{{Quote box|width=250px|align=right|quote=\n\"The first time we cut vocals, my headphones had a little reverb, but there was none on the board when they recorded me. At first, I was mildly freaked out. It sounded so raw. But then I got into the intimacy of how the vocal was presented. In fact, I got into it to the point where I insisted that there be no effects on my vocals anywhere on the album, regardless of the producer.\"\n|source=\u2013Madonna about the vocoder's vocal distortion on the song \"Nobody's Perfect\".<ref name=\"billaugust\"/>}}\n\n''[[Slant Magazine]]''{{'}}s Sal Cinquemani described the album as having a \"more experimental direction\".<ref name=\"slant\"/> With ''[[The Face (magazine)|The Face]]'' magazine, Madonna explained her inspirations behind the songs and the music of ''Music''. She said, \"This record, more than any other records, covers all the areas of my life. I left off partying on ''[[Ray of Light]]''. But I'd just had a baby, so my mood was complete, like wonderment of life, and I was incredibly thoughtful and retrospective and intrigued by the mystical aspects of life.\"<ref name=\"face\">{{cite journal| last=Sawyer| first=Miranda| work=[[The Face (magazine)|The Face]]| title=The Future Sound of London| date=August 2000| page=4| issn=0263-1210| issue=8| volume=43}}</ref> Madonna also summed it up as \"Funky, electronic music blended with futuristic folk. Lots of jangly guitars and moody melancholic lines.\"<ref>''[[Smash Hits]]'', c. September 2000, precise date unknown</ref> \"[[Music (Madonna song)|Music]]\", the title track is the first featured on the record. Starting with Madonna's androgynous voice saying \"Hey Mr. DJ, put a record on, I wanna dance with my baby\". Above this lyric, Madonna's voice electronically manipulated asks \"Do you like to boogie woogie?\". According to Santiago Fouz-Hern\u00e1ndez in his book ''Madonna's Drowned Worlds: New Approaches to Her Cultural Transformations'', \"Music\" is a 'disco anthem, and the beat commands [the people] to get up and dance'. He also said that the song is an expression to her public and it is one of Madonna's catchiest singles of her career.<ref name=\"catch\">{{harvnb|Fouz-Hern\u00e1ndez|Jarman-Ivens|2004|pp=65}}</ref> The second track \"[[Impressive Instant]]\" is a club-savvy stomper marked by futuristic keyboard lines and vocals that darken from distorted, and robotic passages. Madonna claimed that the song was the hardest to write.<ref name=\"billaugust\"/><ref name=\"lib\"/> Madonna sings, \"I like to singy, singy, singy, like a bird on a wingy, wingy, wingy\", with childlike abandon amid a vibrant, celebratory swirl of electronic keyboard riffs and thumpy dance beats.<ref name=\"billaugust\"/>\n\nThe third track, \"Runaway Lover\", is a trance/house rave track. It is one of Madonna's collaborations with William Orbit for the album. The following track, \"I Deserve It\", is an acoustic-framed track that is anchored by a hip-hop inflected groove. Madonna said the track \"has the strangest juxtaposition of this folky, simple song and this high-tech, ominous synth line.\" The song lends weight to rich, introspective lyrics, such as the chorus lines: \"Many miles, many roads I have traveled, fallen down of the way/Many hearts, many years have unraveled, leading up to today.\"  \"Amazing\", the fifth track, is a vibrant tempo-shifter that opens with a soft, music-box-like keyboard/string flourish. The song has been compared by Madonna to \"[[Beautiful Stranger]]\" (1999), saying the reason she fought with her record company to cancel the release as a single was because of the similarity. The sixth track, \"Nobody's Perfect\", includes ethereal vocals and a dreamy keyboard. The following track and second single, \"[[Don't Tell Me (Madonna song)|Don't Tell Me]]\", was written by [[Joe Henry]], Madonna's brother-in-law. He performed and released the track, originally named \"Stop\", on his 2001 album ''Scar''. His wife Melanie sent a demo of the track to her sister, who liked it and recorded her version. It is framed by soft acoustic guitars and subtle keyboard lines.<ref name=\"billaugust\"/> The eighth track and third single, \"[[What It Feels Like for a Girl]]\", comments on female role-playing in society. The following track, \"Paradise (Not for Me)\", has lyrics sung in French, and the lyric \"I can't remember, when I was young, I can't explain if it was wrong\" reflected an artistic palette, \"encompassing diverse musical, textual and visual styles in its lyrics.\"<ref name=\"fouz55\">{{harvnb|Fouz-Hern\u00e1ndez|Jarman-Ivens|2004|pp=55\u201358}}</ref> Musically, it draws influence from [[Edith Piaf]].<ref name=\"billaugust\"/> The song was also included on Mirwais Ahmadza\u00ef's album ''Production''.<ref name=\"face\"/> The tenth and final track on the album, \"Gone\", contrasts acoustic guitars with electronic elements. Soulful vocals give depth to such striking, cautionary lyrics as \"Turn to stone, lose my faith, and I'll be gone.\"<ref name=\"billaugust\"/>\n\n== Artwork ==\n[[File:DWTlosangeles3.jpg|thumb|left|upright|230px|Madonna and her dancers dressed as [[cowboy]]s during the performance of \"[[Don't Tell Me (Madonna song)|Don't Tell Me]]\" on the [[Drowned World Tour]], 2001]]\nFor the artwork for ''Music'', Madonna wore a blue shirt, jeans, red boots and a blue cowboy hat. In it, she faces the camera, while in the background a car and a gas station are seen. The [[Rural area|country]] was a constant theme throughout the design, as the album's title, which was a logo that simulated a buckle, showing the silhouette of a cowboy while riding a horse and a yellow background; the bright colors give a sharp contrast compared to the photograph.<ref name=411mania>{{cite web| title=The Album Covers of Madonna| url=http://www.411mania.com/music/columns/279912| accessdate=July 25, 2013| publisher=411 Mania| date=April 10, 2013| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130725134101/http://www.411mania.com/music/columns/279912| archivedate=July 25, 2013| df=mdy-all}}</ref> Photo sessions were conducted by [[Jean Baptiste Mondino]], who had worked previously with the singer on photoshoots and music videos.<ref>{{harvnb|O'Brien|2009|pp=382\u2013384}}</ref> According to Fouz-Hern\u00e1ndez, the artwork is \"a complete celebration to the field\" western United States.<ref>{{harvnb|Fouz-Hern\u00e1ndez|Jarman-Ivens|2004|p=6}}</ref> He also added that it \"is camp, notably Madonna's combination of Western clothing with expensive shoes and bright red high heels. In particular, there is a clear evocation of [[Judy Garland]] \u2013 a major gay icon \u2013 in the artwork\".<ref>{{harvnb|Fouz-Hern\u00e1ndez|Jarman-Ivens|2004|p=67}}</ref> The art direction and design for the album were done by Kevin Reagan.<ref name=\"2001 Grammy Awards\"/>\n\nThe pictures were shot in Los Angeles, California, in April 2000. In an interview with CNN's ''[[Style with Elsa Klensch]]'', Mondino said that he was the one who had the idea of the western themes for the album, and also stated: \"[Madonna] wasn't sure at first, but I told her that if she didn't like it I won't charge her. But she loved the final result!\".<ref>{{cite episode| title=Interview with Madonna| series=Style with Elsa Klensch| credits= Hosted by Elsa Klansch|network=CNN|date=August 15, 2000}}</ref> Madonna also decided to use her new country style during her public appearances for ''Music''{{'}}s promotion; including jeans, shirts and cowboy hats.<ref>{{Harvnb|Fouz-Hern\u00e1ndez|Jarman-Ivens|2004|pp=128\u2013129}}</ref> On her next tour in 2001, Madonna included a segment based entirely on this ambient.<ref>{{cite web| first=Jose| last= D'Angelo| title=Madonna To Revisit Evita, Geisha Girl, Cowgirl Personas For Tour| url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1444306/madonna-revisit-past-selves.jhtml| accessdate=July 5, 2013| publisher=MTV News| date=June 6, 2001}}</ref> Meanwhile, Fouz-Hern\u00e1ndez explained that \"in this appearance Madonna may be parodying and criticizing Country, which symbolizes among other things, the supremacy of the white man, the ambition of the European pioneers and the [[American Dream]]. However, we do not realize that while recognizing the importance that the country has in American popular culture, and joins a long list of artists who have done this previously.<ref>{{harvnb|Fouz-Hern\u00e1ndez|Jarman-Ivens|2004|p=126}}</ref> Despite this, the cowgirl image of Madonna has become one of her most recognized reinventions.<ref>{{cite web| title=Madonna: Looks Through the Years| url=http://www.vh1.com/photos/gallery/?fid=1582834&pid=2808929| accessdate=July 25, 2013| publisher=[[VH1]]| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020040624/http://www.vh1.com/photos/gallery/?fid=1582834&pid=2808929| archivedate=October 20, 2013| df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| first=Lauren| last=Burvill| title=Top ten most awesome Madonna Looks| url=http://www.thevine.com.au/fashion/collections/top-ten-most-awesome-madonna-looks/| accessdate=July 26, 2013| work=The Vine| date=January 3, 2010| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801005842/http://www.thevine.com.au/fashion/collections/top-ten-most-awesome-madonna-looks| archivedate=August 1, 2012| df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\n[[File:Madonna's Music hat.jpg|thumb|A [[cowgirl]] hat and pink shades, two of the various promotional items produced to support the album's release.]]\n\nOn August 22, 2000, a month before the album's official release, all tracks from ''Music'' were leaked online through [[Napster]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Bychawski|first=Adam|url=http://www.nme.com/news/madonna/4252|title=New Madonna 'Music' now available|work=NME|date=August 22, 2000|accessdate=January 8, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160124193624/http://www.nme.com/news/madonna/4252|archivedate=January 24, 2016}}</ref> The album was finally released September 18, 2000 in the United Kingdom, by [[Maverick Records]].<ref name=\"select\">{{cite journal |journal=Select |title=Album reviews|page=100|author=Morgan, Emma |date=October 2000| issn=0959-8367}}</ref> It was released worldwide on September 19, 2000, under Maverick, and distributed by [[Warner Bros. Records]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Music| url=http://www.madonna.com/discography/index/album/albumId/8/| accessdate=July 26, 2013| work=Icon: Madonna Official Website| publisher=Madonna.com| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622063217/http://www.madonna.com/discography/index/album/albumId/8/| archive-date=June 22, 2011| url-status=dead| df=mdy-all}}</ref> At the same time, it was released as a limited edition which contained a 24-page booklet about the album, a brooch copper with the album's logo and two stickers, wrapped in a linen cloth available in four different colors.<ref>{{cite web| title=Music (Limited edition)| url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00004XQWL| accessdate=July 26, 2013| publisher=[[Amazon.com]]}}</ref> The Japanese edition was published on September 15, 2000, and contained two bonus tracks, \"American Pie\" and \"Cyber-raga\".<ref>{{cite web|script-title=ja:\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30c3\u30af| url=https://www.amazon.co.jp/dp/B000051T35/ref=sr_1_5?ie=UTF8&qid=1374642099&sr=8-5&keywords=madonna+music|trans-title=Music| accessdate=July 26, 2013| publisher=Amazon.co.jp. Amazon Inc.| language=Japanese}}</ref> Additionally, the European version contained only \"American Pie\" as a bonus track.<ref>{{cite web| title=Music|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Music-Madonna/dp/B00004WMXZ/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1374642272&sr=8-1&keywords=madonna+music| accessdate=July 26, 2013| publisher=Amazon.co.uk}}</ref> It was not added as a bonus track except in the United States and Canada.<ref name=\"liner\"/> Madonna commented that \"It was something a certain record company executive twisted my arm into doing\", and said she regretted putting the song on the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/jowhiley/interviews/madonna_1_nov2001.shtml |title=Madonna & Jo Whiley |publisher=[[BBC Radio 1]] |date=November 21, 2001 |accessdate=January 18, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011130195913/http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/jowhiley/interviews/madonna_1_nov2001.shtml |archivedate=November 30, 2001 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Also, users who downloaded the album using Apple's [[QuickTime]] application had exclusive access to two remixes of \"Music\".<ref>{{cite web| first=Matt| last=Hutchison| title=Warner Bros., Maverick and Apple Bring Madonna\u2019s \"Music\" to the Web| url=https://ssl.apple.com/pr/library/2000/09/19Warner-Bros-Maverick-and-Apple-Bring-Madonnas-Music-to-the-Web.html| accessdate=July 26, 2013| publisher=[[Apple Inc.]]| date=September 19, 2000| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130141011/https://ssl.apple.com/pr/library/2000/09/19Warner-Bros-Maverick-and-Apple-Bring-Madonnas-Music-to-the-Web.html| archive-date=January 30, 2016| url-status=dead| df=mdy-all}}</ref> The edition released in Mexico contains as bonus tracks \"Lo Que Siente La Mujer\", a Spanish version of \"What It Feels Like for a Girl\" and a remix of the same song by the group [[Above & Beyond (band)|Above & Beyond]].<ref name=\"mexico\"/> For the Drowned World Tour, it was released as a special edition with a bonus CD with remixes and the video of \"What It Feels Like for a Girl\".<ref name=\"touralbum\"/>\n\nMadonna chatted with fans through her first live chat on [[AOL]] on the day of ''Music''{{'}} release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dotmusic.com/artists/Madonna/news/September2000/news15429.asp |title=Madonna On-Line Live Tonight |date=September 18, 2000 |accessdate=September 19, 2016 |publisher=[[Dotmusic]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001017232051/http://www.dotmusic.com/artists/Madonna/news/September2000/news15429.asp |archivedate=October 17, 2000 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In order to celebrate the album's release, Madonna had a release party at dance emporium Catch One in Los Angeles, California, on September 20, 2000. The \u00a31.4 million party paid by the singer's record company Warner Bros. and ''[[Us (magazine)|Us]]'' magazine was attended by 600 select guests who received special invitations. The party invites were sent out in white leather boxes, lined with black fur. A gold necklace was inside with letters spelling out the album's title, and only those wearing the necklaces would be allowed into the club. More than a dozen strippers were in attendance to keep the party in the same theme as from the music video for \"Music\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dotmusic.com/news/September2000/news15391.asp |title=Madonna Plans Lavish Launch Party |date=September 14, 2000 |accessdate=September 19, 2016 |publisher=Dotmusic |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001216180500/http://dotmusic.com/news/September2000/news15391.asp |archivedate=December 16, 2000 |url-status=dead }}</ref> She sported a five-carat diamond ring Ritchie gave her for her birthday, and a black T-shirt that read \"''[[Snatch (film)|Snatch]]'' Coming Soon\" promoting Ritchie's film, while Ritchie promoted Madonna's album wearing a T-shirt with the word ''Music'' emblazoned on it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/Entertainment-Review-2000-Part-13/9f78e668aa623958541df1c087bf9137?searchfilter=Compilations%2Fap+annual+entertainment+reviews%2FEntertainment+Review+2000%2F19603|title=Entertainment Review 2000: Part 13|date=September 20, 2000|accessdate=September 19, 2016|publisher=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> Among those who attended the party were [[Sheryl Crow]], [[Gwen Stefani]], Maverick Records' head [[Guy Oseary]], and [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]], who arrived with [[Macy Gray]] in a horse-drawn carriage. Madonna's then-boyfriend Guy Ritchie was initially denied access into the VIP lounge by a security guard. He apparently got into a shoving match with a bodyguard who did not know who he was.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://rollingstone.com/sections/news/text/newsarticle.asp?afl=&NewsID=11829&LookUpString=370 |title=Really Randoms: Madonna, Red Hot Chili Peppers |date=September 22, 2000 |accessdate=September 19, 2016 |work=Rolling Stone |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001216214400/http://rollingstone.com/sections/news/text/newsarticle.asp?afl=&NewsID=11829&LookUpString=370 |archivedate=December 16, 2000 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Promotion ==\n\n=== Live performances ===\n[[File:Madonna 02837291 29281 Milan.jpg|thumb|left|Madonna performing promotional single \"[[Impressive Instant]]\" during the [[Drowned World Tour]].|alt=Image of a blond woman wearing a black outfit with a red skirt. She's surrounded by several people wearing gas masks.]]\n\nFollowing the album's release and motherhood, Madonna appeared on ''[[The Late Show with David Letterman]]'' on November 3, 2000, being the first time since her [[Madonna on Late Show with David Letterman|controversial appearance in 1994]], and performed \"Don't Tell Me\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/may/20/david-letterman-best-musical-guests|title=David Letterman was late night's music champion \u2013 and these are his best guests|first=Maura|last=Johnston|date=May 20, 2015|publisher=|via=The Guardian}}</ref> Madonna made a concert on November 5, 2000, at [[Roseland Ballroom]] in New York City. Accompanying musicians performing with Madonna were [[Mirwais Ahmadza\u00ef]] on guitar and longtime backing singers [[Niki Haris]] and [[Donna DeLory]].<ref name=\"nyc\">{{cite web |last=Kemp |first=Rob |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431543/madonna-shatters-record-mostviewed-webcast-producer.jhtml |title=Madonna Shatters Record For Most-Viewed Webcast, Producer Says |work=MTV News |date=November 29, 2000 |accessdate=May 14, 2012}}</ref> The costumes for the show and the set was designed by [[Dolce & Gabbana]]. Songs performed included \"Impressive Instant\", \"Runaway Lover\", \"[[Don't Tell Me (Madonna song)|Don't Tell Me]]\", \"[[What It Feels Like for a Girl]]\", and \"[[Music (Madonna song)|Music]]\". In the performance of New York, she wore a T-shirt with \"[[Britney Spears]]\" written on it.<ref name=\"nyc\"/> She then traveled to Europe to further promote the album. The singer performed \"Don't Tell Me\" on German game-show ''[[Wetten, dass..?]]'' on November 11, 2000.<ref>{{Google books |plainurl= |id=0XSyqXc1bM0C |page=219 |title=Eine au\u00dfersinnliche Odyssee zu Madonna: Das Geheimnis des Feldbewusstseins }}</ref> At the [[MTV Europe Music Awards 2000]], Madonna performed \"Music\" on November 16, 2000 in Stockholm, Sweden. After being introduced by Ali G as \"[[Diego Maradona|Maradona]]\", she performed the song wearing a T-shirt with the name of Australian recording artist [[Kylie Minogue]] printed on it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1027299.stm|title=Madonna's MTV triumph|date=November 17, 2000|accessdate=October 18, 2014|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> She later performed \"Don't Tell Me\" and \"Music\" on British television program ''[[Top of The Pops]]'', in an appearance aired on November 17.<ref>{{cite news|title=Madonna sets TOTP date|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1028455.stm|accessdate=July 15, 2014|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=November 17, 2000}}</ref>\n\nOn November 24, 2000, Madonna performed the latter songs live on French television program ''Nulle Part Ailleurs''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/musique/2015/02/27/03006-20150227ARTFIG00304-madonna-sa-plus-grosse-campagne-promo-depuis-10-ans.php|title=Madonna : sa plus grosse campagne promo depuis 10 ans|first=Aur\u00e9lien|last=Jouhanneau|date=February 27, 2015|publisher=|via=Le Figaro}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lesinrocks.com/2000/11/10/musique/madonna-sur-scene-en-compagnie-de-richard-ashcroft-fatboy-slim-et-liam-howlett-11227461/|title=Les Inrocks \u2013 Madonna sur sc\u00e8ne en compagnie de Richard Ashcroft, Fatboy Slim et Liam Howlett|first=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric|last=Valion|date=November 9, 2000|publisher=}}</ref> Madonna then played another concert on November 29, 2000, at [[Brixton Academy]] in London. It was shown via the internet to an estimated record-breaking 9 million viewers across the world.<ref name=\"londres\">{{cite web| last=Loder| first=Kurt| url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431546/madonna-playful-at-rare-new-york-show.jhtml| title=Madonna Playful At Rare New York Show| work=MTV News| date=November 6, 2000| accessdate=May 14, 2012}}</ref> The setlist was the same from the Roseland Ballroom's concert, with the song \"[[Holiday (Madonna song)|Holiday]]\" being added to the setlist.<ref>{{cite web| last=Schumacher-Rasmussen| first=Eric| url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431543/madonna-shatters-record-mostviewed-webcast-producer.jhtml| title=Madonna Show To Be Webcast Live| work=MTV News| date=November 10, 2000| accessdate=May 14, 2012}}</ref> The singer [[Richard Ashcroft]] and the Scottish band Texas opened the concert.<ref>{{cite web| last=Schumacher-Rasmussen| first=Eric| url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431545/madonna-show-be-webcast-live.jhtml| title=Madonna Show To Be Webcast Live| work=MTV News| date=November 10, 2000| accessdate=May 14, 2012}}</ref> Madonna then performed \"Don't Tell Me\" on ''Carr\u00e0mba! Che fortuna'' in Italy, on December 2, 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.madonna.com/news/title/madonna-performs-on-carramba-che-fortuna-show-italy|title=Madonna performs on Carramba Che Fortuna Show, Italy|publisher=}}</ref> On February 21, 2001, she performed \"Music\" at the [[43rd Grammy Awards]].<ref name=basham>{{cite web| last=Basham| first=David| url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1439793/madonna-shell-mount-summer-tour.jhtml| title=Madonna Says She'll Mount Summer Tour| work=MTV News| date=February 23, 2001| accessdate=May 14, 2012}}</ref> For the performance, the stage had five giant video screens, which showed images from her career. Madonna entered onto the stage in a classic [[Cadillac]] driven by rapper [[Bow Wow (rapper)|Bow Wow]]. The singer emerged from the back seat of the car in a full-length fur coat and a hat, quickly removing the clothes to reveal a tight leather jacket and jeans.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chrisafulli|first=Chuck|url=http://www.madonna.com/news/title/madonna-prepares-for-high-energy-grammy-performance|title=Madonna prepares for high-energy Grammy performance|date=February 21, 2001|accessdate=October 18, 2014|publisher=Madonna.com}}</ref> She removed her jacket to reveal a black tank top with the words \"Material Girl\" printed on it.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fury|first=Jeanne|url=http://www.nyrock.com/features/2001/grammy.asp|title=God to Grammy Winners: Don't Thank Me for That Lousy Song|publisher=NY Rock|accessdate=October 18, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303205652/http://www.nyrock.com/features/2001/grammy.asp|archivedate=March 3, 2016}}</ref> Host [[Jon Stewart]] commented right after, talking about how he was getting older and commenting, \"As I was watching Madonna writhing around on the hood of the car, all I could think was \u2014 that\u2019s really gonna drive up her insurance premiums\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/awards/43rd-annual-grammy-awards|title=43rd Annual Grammy Awards|accessdate=October 18, 2014|publisher=National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences}}</ref>\n\n=== Tour ===\n{{Main|Drowned World Tour}}\nTo promote ''Music'' and ''Ray of Light'', Madonna embarked on her fifth concert tour, the [[Drowned World Tour]]. It started in June 2001 and was Madonna's first tour in eight years since [[The Girlie Show World Tour]] (1993). The tour was to be started before the year 2000,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/SHOWBIZ/Music/9901/19/madonna.lkl/| title=Interview: Madonna reviews life on Larry King Live| date=January 19, 1999| work=CNN| accessdate=December 28, 2009| last=King| first=Larry| authorlink=Larry King}}</ref> but she had become pregnant with her son Rocco Ritchie, released ''Music'' that year, and married [[Guy Ritchie]] in December 2000.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601085&sid=aZUOJ_MvDaRI&refer=europe| title=Madonna, Guy Ritchie Divorce Approved by U.K. Court| last=Lumley| first=James| date=November 21, 2008| work=[[Bloomberg Television]]| accessdate=December 28, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Guilbert|2002|p=76}}</ref> When Madonna finally decided to go on the tour, time was short and she had to prepare the show within three months. [[Jamie King]] was signed up as the creative director and the choreographer of the show.<ref>{{harvnb|Metz|Benson|1999|p=67}}</ref> The tour was divided into five segments, namely [[punk rock|punk]], [[geisha]], [[cowboy]], [[Latin music (genre)|Latin]] and [[ghetto]]. Each segment represented a phase of Madonna's career. Several changes were made to the final shows in Los Angeles after the [[September 11 attacks]]: Madonna wore an American flag kilt during the show's opening segment as a display of [[patriotism]], the closing of \"Mer Girl\" (part II) was altered to remove the staged shooting of a character; Madonna instead put the gun down, hugged him and they left the stage together. The macabre cannibalism-themed \"Funny Song\" was removed.<ref name=\"fouz\">{{harvnb|Fouz-Hern\u00e1ndez|Jarman-Ivens|2004|p=133}}</ref> The tour received positive reviews.<ref name=\"inder\">{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/madonna-earls-court-london-677159.html| title=Madonna, Earls Court, London| last=Price| first=Simon| date=July 9, 2001| work=[[The Independent]]| accessdate=December 30, 2009}}</ref> The tour was a commercial success, grossing a total of US$75 million, and it was the highest-grossing concert tour of a solo artist in 2001.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1451603/20011221/u2.jhtml |title=U2, 'NSYNC, Backstreet Top List Of 2001's Biggest Concert Grossers |last=Wiederhorn |first=Jon |date=December 21, 2001 |work=MTV News |accessdate=December 31, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090910074239/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1451603/20011221/u2.jhtml |archivedate=September 10, 2009 }}</ref> The tour received the Major Tour of the Year and Most Creative Stage Production awards nominations at the [[Pollstar|2001 Pollstar awards]], but lost them to U2.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.pollstarpro.com/PCIA-Static/awards2001.htm| title=Pollstar Awards Archive \u2013 2001| accessdate=December 31, 2009| publisher=[[Pollstar]]}}</ref> The concert was broadcast live on [[HBO]] from [[The Palace of Auburn Hills]] in [[Auburn Hills, Michigan]]  August 26, 2001.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1444026/20010524/madonna.jhtml| title=Madonna Bringing Drowned World To HBO| last=Schumacher-Rasmussen| first=Eric| date=May 24, 2001| work=MTV News}}</ref> The ''[[Drowned World Tour 2001]]'' DVD was released in all regions on November 13, 2001.<ref>{{harvnb|Guilbert|2002|p=189}}</ref>\n\n=== Singles ===\n\"[[Music (Madonna song)|Music]]\" was released as the lead single from the album on August 21, 2000 by [[Warner Bros. Records]]. \"Music\" has been praised by contemporary critics. Some compared it with Madonna's older songs, like \"[[Into the Groove]] (1985) and \"[[Holiday (Madonna song)|Holiday]]\" (1983).<ref name=sal>{{cite web| url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/madonna-music/117| title=Madonna \u2013 Music| last=Cinquemani| first=Sal| date=August 21, 2000| accessdate=May 7, 2012| work=[[Slant Magazine]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,255548_2,00.html| title=The Girl Material| date=July 27, 2001| accessdate=May 7, 2012| work=Entertainment Weekly}}</ref> \"Music\" achieved international success by topping the charts in 25 countries worldwide.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/lifestyle/news/article.cfm?c_id=6&objectid=153363| title=Madonna's Music is sweet to world's ears| date=September 30, 2000|accessdate=August 10, 2010| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]}}</ref> It became Madonna's 12th number-one single on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], making Madonna the second artist to achieve number one hits in the 1980s, 1990s, and 2000s on the Hot 100. In the United Kingdom, \"Music\" peaked at number one on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref name=ukpeak>{{cite web| url=http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/2000-09-02/| title=Top 40 Official UK Singles Archive|work=[[UK Singles Chart]]| publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]]| date=September 2, 2000| accessdate=May 6, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/731080.stm| title=Ali G 'stars in Madonna video'| work=[[BBC News]]| date=April 30, 2000| accessdate=May 14, 2012}}</ref> \"[[Don't Tell Me (Madonna song)|Don't Tell Me]]\" was released on November 21, 2000 as the second single from the album. It reached at number four and spent eight weeks in the top ten of the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name=\"billbmadonna\">{{cite web |url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=madonna|chart=all}} |title=Don't Tell Me |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=May 17, 2010}}</ref> The song topped the music charts in the Canada, Italy and New Zealand and attained top-ten positions on the charts of many other European nations.<ref name=\"ultratop\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Madonna&titel=Don%27t+Tell+Me&cat=s |work=Ultratop |title=Don't Tell Me \u2013 Madonna |accessdate=May 17, 2010}}</ref> In 2005, the song was placed at number 285 on ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]'' magazine's The 500 Greatest Songs Since You Were Born.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blender.com/lists/68125/500-greatest-songs-since-you-were-born-251-300.html?p=5 |title=The 500 Greatest Songs Since You Were Born (251\u2013300) |work=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]] |accessdate=May 17, 2010 |date=January 4, 2009 }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n\"[[What It Feels Like for a Girl]]\" was released as the third and final single from the album, on April 17, 2001. It received positive appreciation from contemporary critics. The song lost the top-twenty on the official chart of the United States, but it was a success on the US dance charts.<ref>{{cite web |url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=madonna|chart=all}} |title=What It Feels Like for a Girl \u2013 Madonna |work=Billboard |accessdate=May 12, 2012}}</ref> The music video, directed by [[Guy Ritchie]], portrays Madonna as an angry woman on a crime spree. Reviewers criticized the video for being overly violent and graphic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://new.music.yahoo.com/madonna/news/artist-name-madonna-id-1016600-video-to-air-one-time-only-due-to-violent-content--12038004 |title=Video To Air One Time Only Due To Violent Content |publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]] |date=March 20, 2001 |accessdate=November 23, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110319080117/http://new.music.yahoo.com/madonna/news/artist-name-madonna-id-1016600-video-to-air-one-time-only-due-to-violent-content--12038004 |archivedate=March 19, 2011 }}</ref> The video was banned from most North American and European video stations, receiving only early hours play.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/5209714.stm| work=BBC News| title=Madonna video 'top rule-breaker'| date=July 24, 2006}}</ref> \"[[Impressive Instant]]\" was released as a club promo only single with remixes by [[Peter Rauhofer]] on September 18, 2001.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=199327 |title=Madonna Impressive Instant USA Promo 12\" Record/Maxi Single (199327) |publisher=Eil.com |accessdate=July 10, 2010}}</ref> It went to number one on the [[Hot Dance Club Play]] chart where it stayed for two weeks.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/56709/chart-beat| title=Chart Beat: Bump For 'Jump'| last=Bronson| first=Fred| authorlink=Fred Bronson| date=September 13, 2006| accessdate=August 26, 2009| work=Billboard}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/56709/chart-beat |title=Chart Beat |work=Billboard |accessdate=August 23, 2011}}</ref> The song was intended by Madonna to be released as the fourth single off ''Music'' but Madonna's recording company wanted \"Amazing\" to be the next single. Madonna felt that \"Amazing\" was too similar to her previous single \"[[Beautiful Stranger]]\" (1999), so they were deadlocked.<ref name=\"amazing\">{{cite episode |series=Monte-Carlo 102.1 FM |credits=[[Sasha (DJ)|DJ Sasha]]. Denis Zaharov |network=[[Radio Monte Carlo]] |station=102.1 FM |location=Moscow |date=May 21, 2003 |season= |seriesno= |number= |minutes=23 |time= |quote=Well, it's a bit complicated when the choices of the artist and the ones of the record company don't match&nbsp;... |language=Russian}}</ref> Warner Bros. planned to move forward with the release of \"Amazing\" without Madonna's help since she was too busy preparing for her next tour, and planned to promote the single with a [[music video]] cut from the live version of \"Amazing\" from Madonna's [[Drowned World Tour]], but she scrapped the song from the set list to be sure that Warner Bros. could not promote it, and the fourth single idea was over.<ref name=\"amazing\"/>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 80/100<ref name=\"metacritic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/music/madonna|title=Reviews for Music by Madonna|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=April 2, 2009}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic1\">{{cite web|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/music-mw0000088531|title=Music \u2013 Madonna|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=August 21, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Blender\">{{cite journal|last=Power|first=Tony|url=http://www.blender.com/reviews/review_2348.html|title=Madonna: Music|journal=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]|location=New York|issue=22|date=December 2003|accessdate=June 7, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040818000328/http://www.blender.com/reviews/review_2348.html|archivedate=August 18, 2004|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3Score = B<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite journal|last=Browne|first=David|authorlink=David Browne (journalist)|date=September 24, 2000|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2000/09/18/music|title=Music|journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|location=New York|accessdate=September 22, 2015|pages=72\u201373|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706163219/http://ew.com/article/2000/09/18/music-2/|archivedate=July 6, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Mulholland|first=Garry|date=September 15, 2000|url=https://www.theguardian.com/friday_review/story/0,3605,368337,00.html|title=Set adrift in a sea of skronks|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|accessdate=June 7, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Melody Maker]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=Madonna: Music|journal=[[Melody Maker]]|location=London|date=September 26, 2000|page=50}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6Score = 8/10<ref name=\"nme\">{{cite journal|last=Segal|first=Victoria|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/madonna/2810|title=Music|journal=[[NME]]|location=London|date=September 15, 2000|accessdate=May 14, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080423021617/http://www.nme.com/reviews/madonna/2810|archivedate=April 23, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Qmag\">{{cite journal|last=Eccleston|first=Danny|date=October 2000|url=http://www.qonline.co.uk/reviews/server.asp?id=18961|title=Madonna: Music|journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|location=London|issue=169|accessdate=September 11, 2016|pages=108\u201309|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001205203200/http://www.qonline.co.uk/reviews/server.asp?id=18961|archivedate=December 5, 2000|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"rs\">{{cite journal|last=Walters|first=Barry|date=October 12, 2000|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/music-20001012|title=Music|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|location=New York|accessdate=August 21, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev9Score = 7/10<ref name=\"spin\">{{cite journal|last=Pappademas|first=Alex|date=October 2000|title=Madonna: Music|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HTMuhxamaFEC&pg=PA173|journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|location=New York|volume=16|issue=10|accessdate=May 14, 2012|page=173|issn=0886-3032}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| rev10Score = A<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=October 24, 2000|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv1000-00.php|title=Consumer Guide: Ina Dancehall Groove--Finally|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|location=New York|accessdate=September 22, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nAt [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream publications, the album received an [[weighted arithmetic mean|average]] score of 80, based on 16 reviews, indicating \"generally favorable reviews.\"<ref name=\"metacritic\"/> [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[AllMusic]] praised the album's layered music and described Madonna's collaboration with Mirwais as the reason why the album \"comes alive with spark and style\".<ref name=\"allmusic1\"/> Dimitri Ehrlich from ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' called the album \"a masterpiece of brilliantly arranged keyboards, futuristic drums, and electronica dressings. With folky acoustic guitars and a vaguely spiritual bent to her lyrics (like those on ''Ray of Light''), it's a weird and fresh-sounding album.\"<ref name=\"vibe\">{{cite journal| last=Ehrlich| first=Dimitri|title=Madonna \u2013 Music| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-CcEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA173#v=onepage&q&f=false| journal=Vibe| issn=1070-4701| accessdate=May 14, 2012}}</ref> Andrew Lynch of Entertainment.ie, who gave the album three out of five stars, claimed that it contains \"brilliant futuristic dance music\", yet, claimed that the lyrics were \"trite\".<ref name=\"entertainment1\">{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.ie/album-review/Madonna---Music/797.htm |title=Madonna \u2013 Music. Review by Andrew Lynch |publisher=Entertainment.ie |date=September 28, 2000 |accessdate=September 15, 2014}}</ref> [[Robert Christgau]] from ''[[The Village Voice]]'' said the record has \"consistency and flow\" because all of its songs are good and [[wikt:lowbrow|lowbrow]]: \"From Vocoder to cowgirl suit, she's got her sass back.\"<ref name=\"Christgau\"/> [[David Browne (journalist)|David Browne]] was less enthusiastic in ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', calling it \"her most patchwork record since the [[Sean Penn]] years... In the way it tiptoes around sundry moods and beats, ''Music'' is frustratingly inconsistent, as if Madonna herself weren't sure where to venture next. At times, it feels like a collection of sounds -- clever, intriguing ones, to be sure -- that seek to compensate for ordinary melodies and Madonna's stoic delivery.\"<ref name=\"EW\"/>\n\n''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' said that the album \"is a much-needed breath of fresh VapoRub.\"<ref name=\"spin\"/> Danny Eccleston, in a review for ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'', called it a \"brave, radical and punchy (at a refreshing 49 minutes in length) album\".<ref name=\"Qmag\"/> A retrospective review in ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]'' remarked: \"Her first 'headphones album'... It's more playful and less pompous than ''Ray of Light''.\"<ref name=\"Blender\"/> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' stated that the album was a rough and improvised version of ''Ray of Light'', but lauded that Madonna had chosen to make a more \"instinctive\" record than her previous endeavours.<ref name=\"rs\"/> ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'' magazine said that \"''Music'' is fitful and its charms aren't all immediate, but Madonna is still doing what she does best--giving a lick of pop genius to the unlikely genre of experimental dance music.\"<ref name=\"metacritic\"/> ''[[NME]]'' said that ''Music'' is \"vocodered, stretched, distorted, warped, deliberately upstaged by beats so showy they belong in a strip joint \u2013 quite simply, she's almost managed to make herself disappear. That bluntly explicit title isn't just pointless irony. This record is about the music, not Madonna; about the sounds, not the image.\"<ref name=\"nme\"/> ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' criticised Madonna's collaborations with William Orbit, who had worked with her on ''Ray of Light'', calling them repetitive and uninteresting despite being catchy.<ref name=\"slant\">{{cite web| url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/music_review.asp?ID=119| title=Madonna \u2013 Music| work=Slant Magazine| date=August 20, 2001| accessdate=May 14, 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222165726/http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/music_review.asp?ID=119| archivedate=February 22, 2014| df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2015, [[Rob Sheffield]] of ''Rolling Stone'' said that ''Music'' is \"still [Madonna's] hardest-rocking and most seductive album.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Rob Sheffield]]|title=Bitch, She's Madonna: NYC Stop Showcases Genius of Rebel Heart Tour|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/bitch-shes-madonna-nyc-stop-showcases-genius-of-rebel-heart-tour-20150917|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=September 17, 2015|accessdate=October 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''Music'' was voted the 16th best record of 2001 in ''The Village Voice''{{'}}s [[Pazz & Jop]], an annual poll of American critics published by ''The Village Voice''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/pnj/pjres00.php|title=Pazz & Jop 2000: Critics Poll|newspaper=The Village Voice|location=New York|year=2001|accessdate=September 22, 2015}}</ref> The album earned Madonna a total of five [[Grammy Award]] nominations. In 2001, it won \"[[Grammy Award for Best Recording Package|Best Recording Package]]\" and was nominated for \"[[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album|Best Pop Vocal Album]]\", while the title track was nominated for \"[[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]]\" and \"[[Grammy Award for Best Female Pop Vocal Performance|Best Female Pop Vocal Performance]]\".<ref name=\"2001 Grammy Awards\">{{cite web| url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=&field_nominee_work_value=&a%C3%B1o=2000&genre=22&=Search| publisher=National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences| title=Past Winners Search| accessdate=May 5, 2012}}</ref> In 2002, Madonna received one more nomination for \"Don't Tell Me\" in the \"[[Grammy Award for Best Short Form Music Video|Best Short Form Music Video]]\" category. On ''NME''{{'}}s list of the 50 best albums of 2000, ''Music'' was ranked at number 47.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nme.com/photos/a-decade-in-music-50-best-albums-of-2000/156888/1/1#4| title=A decade in music \u2013 50 best albums of 2000| work=NME| accessdate=July 30, 2014}}</ref> In 2003, the album is listed at number 452 on ''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time]]. It is Madonna's fourth album on the list, the most among female artists.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-19691231/music-madonna-19691231 |title=500 Greatest Albums: Music \u2013 Madonna | work=Rolling Stone |date=May 31, 2012 |accessdate= September 15, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101219094110/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-19691231/music-madonna-19691231| archivedate=December 19, 2010}}</ref> ''Music'' is also featured in the book ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1001beforeyoudie.com |title=1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die |publisher=[[Quintessence Editions Ltd.]] |year=2003 |accessdate=November 25, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101119080055/http://1001beforeyoudie.com/ |archivedate=November 19, 2010 }}</ref> ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' included the album on their list of \"The Best Albums of the Aughts\" at number 31.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.slantmagazine.com/features/article/best-of-the-aughts-albums/P14||title= The Best Albums of the Aughts| accessdate= February 19, 2016|work=Slant Magazine}}</ref> ''[[Spin Magazine]]'' named \"Music\" the 18th best album of the year 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/2000/12/20-best-albums-2000/madonna-music/||title= The 20 Best Albums of 2000| accessdate= February 19, 2016| work=Spin | publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== Commercial performance ==\nTen days after the album's release, [[CNN]] reported that it had sold over four million copies worldwide.<ref name=\"cnn\">{{cite news|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/2000/SHOWBIZ/Music/11/10/wb.madonna.album/index.html |work=CNN |title=Madonna's secret to making 'Music' |date=November 10, 2000 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130618234026/http://transcripts.cnn.com/2000/SHOWBIZ/Music/11/10/wb.madonna.album/index.html |archivedate=June 18, 2013 }}</ref> The album set a record in Warner Music Group as the biggest album shipment in the company, with three million copies worldwide in the first week.<ref name=\"companyrecord\">{{cite news| url= http://www.timewarner.com/newsroom/press-releases/2000/09/26/madonna-s-music-sets-new-wmi-shipment-record|title=Madonna's MUSIC Sets New WMI Shipment Record| date=September 26, 2000|publisher=[[Time Warner]]| accessdate=March 31, 2017}}</ref> ''Music'' debuted at number-one in 23 countries. It debuted at the top of the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] with over 420,000 copies sold. It became the first Madonna album to reach the top of the charts in eleven years in the region, since ''[[Like a Prayer (album)|Like a Prayer]]'' (1989).<ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/news/after-11-year-absence-madonnas-back-876212.story| title=After 11 Year Absence, Madonna's Back At No. 1| date=September 28, 2000| last= Caulfield| first=Keith|work=Billboard| accessdate=January 20, 2009}}</ref> The album was certified [[RIAA certification|three times platinum]] by the Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA) on November 21, 2005.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=madonna&format=ALBUM&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2009&sort=Artist&perPage=25| title=Gold & Platinum Database&nbsp;\u2013 Madonna| date=November 21, 2005| accessdate=May 14, 2012| publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6A0rW9Q0c?url=http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=madonna&format=ALBUM&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec| archivedate=August 18, 2012| df=mdy-all}}</ref> As of August 2010, ''Music'' has sold 2,925,000 copies there according to [[Nielsen SoundScan]].<ref>{{cite web| last= Grein| first=Paul| url=http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart-watch/week-ending-aug-15-2010-the-odd-couple.html| title=Week Ending Aug. 15, 2010: The Odd Couple| publisher=Yahoo! Music| date=August 18, 2010| accessdate=May 14, 2012}}</ref> In Canada, the album debuted at the top of the [[RPM (magazine)|Canadian ''RPM'' Albums Chart]] and was certified platinum by the [[Music Canada|Canadian Recording Industry Association]] (CRIA) for shipments of 300,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.cria.ca/gold/0701_g.php |title=Gold & Platinum Certification \u2013 July 2001 |website= Cria.ca |accessdate=August 21, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141008040242/http://www.cria.ca/gold/0701_g.php |archivedate=October 8, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThroughout Europe, the album also did well on its charts. On October 1, 2000, ''Music'' debuted at number one on the Austrian Albums Chart, spending a total of forty weeks in the chart.<ref name=\"aut\"/> The song achieved relatively good charting in both the Flemish and Wallonian territories in Belgium, peaking at numbers two and four, respectively.<ref name=\"bel\"/> On the [[French Albums Chart]], the album debuted at number one, staying 67 weeks on the chart, before falling out on June 29, 2002.<ref name=frchar/> The song was certified twice platinum by the [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]] (SNEP).<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.infodisc.fr/CD_Certif.php |title=InfoDisc: Les Certifications (Albums) du SNEP (Bilan par Artiste) |publisher= [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]] |language=French |accessdate=May 14, 2012 |trans-title=Infodisc: Certifications (Albums) SNEP (Bilan by Artist) |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090601152354/http://www.infodisc.fr/CD_Certif.php |archivedate=June 1, 2009 }}</ref> ''Music'' debuted at number one on the [[UK Albums Chart]].<ref name=\"uk\"/> The album was certified five times platinum by the [[British Phonographic Industry]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx |title=BPI \u2013 Certified Awards Search |work=[[British Phonographic Industry]] |accessdate=September 24, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090924015932/http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx |archivedate=September 24, 2009 }}</ref> On September 28, 2000, ''Music'' debuted at number one on the [[Swedish Singles Chart]], before falling out at number 52.<ref name=\"swe\"/> Similarly in Switzerland, the album also peaked at number one, and spent 42 weeks fluctuating inside the chart.<ref name=\"swi\"/>\n\nIn Australia, ''Music'' peaked at number two on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Albums Chart]] failing to reach the top spot due to the success of ''[[The Games of the XXVII Olympiad: Official Music from the Opening Ceremony]]''.<ref name=\"aus\"/> The album was certified three times platinum by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA).<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-accreditations-albums-2001.htm |title=ARIA |publisher=ARIA |accessdate=August 21, 2011}}</ref> In New Zealand, ''Music'' debuted and peaked at number two on October 8, 2000, staying on the chart for thirty-three weeks.<ref name=\"nz\"/> The album debuted at number seven on the Oricon weekly album chart in Japan.<ref name=\"oricon\"/> The album was awarded at the Hong Kong Record Sales Award 2001 by the [[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry|IFPI Hong Kong]] for becoming one of ten biggest-selling international album of the year.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.ifpihk.org/www_1/go23e.php|title=Gold Disc Award > Gold Disc Award Criteria|publisher=[[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry|IFPI Hong Kong]]|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> It was the 19th best-selling album of 2001 worldwide.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FBAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA42|title=Dido, Linkin Park Lead the Global 20 of 2001|last=White|first=Adam|date=February 16, 2002|accessdate=February 16, 2016|work=Billboard|issn=0006-2510| page= 42| volume= 114|issue=7}}</ref> Worldwide sales are more than eleven million copies.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.nbcwashington.com/the-scene/archive/Madonnas_Hard_Candy_Strikes_Sour_Note.html|title=Madonna\u2019s 'Hard Candy' Strikes Sour Note|last=Gerard|first=Chris|date=July 15, 2009|accessdate=August 10, 2010|work=[[WRC-TV]]| location=Washington}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| headline        = ''Music'' {{nobold|\u2013 Standard edition}}\n| title1          = [[Music (Madonna song)|Music]]\n| writer1         = {{hlist|[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]|[[Mirwais Ahmadza\u00ef]]}}\n| extra1          = {{hlist|Madonna|Ahmadza\u00ef}}\n| length1         = 3:44\n| title2          = [[Impressive Instant]]\n| writer2         = {{hlist|Madonna|Ahmadza\u00ef}}\n| extra2          = {{hlist|Madonna|Ahmadza\u00ef}}\n| length2         = 3:37\n| title3          = Runaway Lover\n| writer3         = {{hlist|Madonna|[[William Orbit]]}}\n| extra3          = {{hlist|Madonna|Orbit}}\n| length3         = 4:46\n| title4          = I Deserve It\n| writer4         = {{hlist|Madonna|Ahmadza\u00ef}}\n| extra4          = {{hlist|Madonna|Ahmadza\u00ef}}\n| length4         = 4:23\n| title5          = Amazing\n| writer5         = {{hlist|Madonna|Orbit}}\n| extra5          = {{hlist|Madonna|Orbit}}\n| length5         = 3:43\n| title6          = Nobody's Perfect\n| writer6         = {{hlist|Madonna|Ahmadza\u00ef}}\n| extra6          = {{hlist|Madonna|Ahmadza\u00ef}}\n| length6         = 4:58\n| title7          = [[Don't Tell Me (Madonna song)|Don't Tell Me]]\n| writer7         = {{hlist|Madonna|Ahmadza\u00ef|[[Joe Henry]]}}\n| extra7          = {{hlist|Madonna|Ahmadza\u00ef}}\n| length7         = 4:40\n| title8          = [[What It Feels Like for a Girl]]\n| writer8         = {{hlist|Madonna|[[Guy Sigsworth]]|[[David Torn]]}}\n| extra8          = {{hlist|Madonna|Sigsworth|[[Spike Stent|Mark \"Spike\" Stent]]}}\n| length8         = 4:43\n| title9          = Paradise (Not for Me)\n| writer9         = {{hlist|Ahmadza\u00ef|Madonna}}\n| extra9          = {{hlist|Ahmadza\u00ef|Madonna}}\n| length9         = 6:33\n| title10         = Gone\n| writer10        = {{hlist|Madonna|[[Damian LeGassick]]|Nik Young}}\n| extra10         = {{hlist|Madonna|Orbit|Stent}}\n| length10        = 3:24\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        = ''Music'' {{nobold|\u2013 International edition (bonus track)}}<ref name=\"liner\"/>\n| title11         = [[American Pie (song)#Madonna version|American Pie]]\n| writer11        = [[Don McLean]]\n| extra11         = {{hlist|Madonna|Orbit}}\n| length11        = 4:33\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        = ''Music'' {{nobold|\u2013 Japanese and Australian edition (bonus tracks)}}<ref>{{cite AV media notes| others=Madonna| title=Music| year=2001| type=Liner notes| publisher=Maverick Records| id=WPCR-75528}}</ref>\n| title12         = Cyber-Raga\n| writer12        = {{hlist|Madonna|[[Talvin Singh]]}} {{small|(adapted from traditional text)}}\n| extra12         = {{hlist|Madonna|Singh}}\n| length12        = 5:33\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| collapsed   = yes\n| headline        = ''Music'' {{nobold|\u2013 Mexican edition (bonus tracks)}}<ref name=\"mexico\">{{cite AV media notes| others=Madonna| title=Music| year=2001| type=Liner notes| publisher=Maverick Records| id=9362-48135-2}}</ref>\n| title11         = Lo Que Siente La Mujer\n| note11           = What It Feels Like for a Girl\n| writer11         = Madonna, Sigsworth {{small|(Spanish translation: Alberto Ferraras)}}\n| extra11          = {{hlist|Madonna|Sigsworth|Stent}}\n| length11         = 4:44\n| title12  = What It Feels Like for a Girl\n| writer12         = {{hlist|Madonna|Sigsworth}}\n| extra12          = {{hlist|Madonna|Sigsworth|Stent}}\n| note12   = [[Above & Beyond (band)|Above & Beyond]] Club Radio Edit\n| length12         = 3:45\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column    = Remixer(s)/Producer(s)\n| collapsed       = yes\n|headline         = ''Music'' {{nobold|\u2013 2001 Special Tour edition (bonus CD)}}<ref name=\"touralbum\">{{cite AV media notes| others=Madonna| title=Music| year=2001| type=Liner notes| publisher=Maverick Records|id=9362481352}}</ref>\n| title1          = [[Music (Madonna song)|Music]]\n| note1           = Deep Dish Dot Com Remix\n| writer1         = {{hlist|Madonna|Ahmadza\u00ef}}\n| extra1          = Dubfire and Sharam for [[Deep Dish (band)|Deep Dish]]\n| length1         = 11:22\n| title2          = Music\n| note2           = HQ2 Club Mix\n| writer2         = {{hlist|Madonna|Ahmadza\u00ef}}\n| extra2          = {{hlist|[[Hex Hector]]|Mac Quayle}}\n| length2         = 8:51\n| title3          = [[Don't Tell Me (Madonna song)|Don't Tell Me]]\n| note3           = Timo Maas Mix\n| writer3         = {{hlist|Madonna|Ahmadza\u00ef|Henry}}\n| extra3          = {{hlist|[[Timo Maas]]|Martin Buttrich}}\n| length3         = 6:55\n| title4          = Don't Tell Me\n| note4           = Tracy Young Club Mix\n| writer4         = {{hlist|Madonna|Ahmadza\u00ef|Henry}}\n| extra4          = {{hlist|Tracy Young|Chris Crane}} {{small|(co-producer)}}\n| length4         = 11:00\n| title5          = [[What It Feels Like for a Girl]]\n| note5           = Paul Oakenfold Perfecto Mix\n| writer5         = {{hlist|Madonna|Sigsworth}}\n| extra5          = {{hlist|[[Paul Oakenfold]]|Andy Gray}}\n| length5         = 7:20\n| title6          = Lo Que Siente La Mujer\n| note6           = What It Feels Like for a Girl\n| writer6         = {{hlist|Madonna|Sigsworth}} {{small|(Spanish translation: Alberto Ferraras)}}\n| extra6          = {{hlist|Madonna|Sigsworth|Stent}}\n| length6         = 4:44\n| title7          = What It Feels Like for a Girl\n| note7           = video\n| writer7         = {{hlist|Madonna|Sigsworth|Torn}}\n| extra7          = Above & Beyond\n| length7         = 4:36\n}}\n'''Notes'''\n*[[David Torn]] was not credited on the original liner notes of ''Music''. Madonna added him as a co-writer of \"What It Feels Like for a Girl\" after she found out Sigsworth had sampled from Torn's 1987 album, ''[[Cloud About Mercury]]'', without her knowledge.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ascap.com/repertory#ace/search/workID/530538722|title=ACE Repertory: Work ID 530538722|publisher=[[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers]]|accessdate=November 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|year=2012|last1=Prasad|first1=Anil|title=David Torn \u2013 Intersecting ambitions|url=http://www.innerviews.org/inner/torn4.html|accessdate=April 26, 2018|work=Innerviews|authorlink=Anil Prasad|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411174952/http://www.innerviews.org/inner/torn4.html|archivedate=April 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Personnel ==\nCredits adapted from the album's liner notes.<ref name=\"liner\">{{cite AV media notes| others=Madonna| title=Music| year=2000| type=Liner notes| publisher=Maverick Records| id=93624-78652-8}}</ref>\n\n===Musicians===\n{{div col}}\n* Madonna \u2013 vocals, guitars\n* Steve Sidelnyk \u2013 drums\n* [[Guy Sigsworth]] \u2013 guitars, keyboards, programming\n* [[William Orbit]] \u2013 keyboards, guitars, programming, backing vocals\n* [[Mirwais Ahmadza\u00ef]] \u2013 guitars, keyboards, programming\n* Sean Spuehler \u2013 programming\n* [[Michel Colombier]] \u2013 string arrangement\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Technical===\n{{div col}}\n* Madonna \u2013 production\n* William Orbit \u2013 production {{small|(tracks: 3, 5, 10)}}\n* Guy Sigsworth \u2013 production {{small|(track 8)}}\n* Mirwais Ahmadza\u00ef \u2013 production {{small|(tracks: 1, 2, 4, 6, 7, 9)}}\n* [[Spike Stent|Mark \"Spike\" Stent]] \u2013 production {{small|(tracks: 8, 10)}}; mixing\n* Jake Davies \u2013 engineering\n* [[Mark Endert]] \u2013 engineering\n* [[Geoff Foster]] \u2013 engineering, string engineer\n* Sean Spuehler \u2013 engineering\n* Tim Lambert \u2013 engineering assistance\n* Chris Ribando \u2013 engineering assistance\n* Dan Vickers \u2013 engineering assistance\n* Tim Young \u2013 mastering\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Artwork===\n{{div col}}\n* Kevin Reagan \u2013 art direction, design\n* Matthew Lindauer \u2013 design\n* [[Jean-Baptiste Mondino]] \u2013 photography\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Charts ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n=== Weekly charts ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2000)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{album chart|Australia|2|artist=Madonna|album=Music|rowheader=true|accessdate=December 16, 2017|refname=\"aus\"}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Austria|1|artist=Madonna|album=Music|rowheader=true|accessdate=December 16, 2017|refname=\"aut\"}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Flanders|2|artist=Madonna|album=Music|rowheader=true|accessdate=December 16, 2017|refname=\"bel\"}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Wallonia|2|artist=Madonna|album=Music|rowheader=true|accessdate=December 16, 2017|refname=\