ne hits of 2000 (Germany)]]\n*[[List of number-one hits of 2000 (Italy)]]\n*[[List of number-one albums of 2000 (Poland)]]\n*[[List of number-one albums of 2000 (U.S.)]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite book\n|last=Fouz-Hern\u00e1ndez\n|first=Santiago\n|first2=Freya\n|last2=Jarman-Ivens\n|title=Madonna's Drowned Worlds\n|publisher=[[Ashgate Publishing]], Ltd.\n|isbn=0-7546-3372-1\n|year=2004\n|ref=harv\n|url-access=registration\n|url=https://archive.org/details/madonnasdrownedw0000unse\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n|last=Metz\n|first=Andrew\n|first2=Carol\n|last2=Benson\n|title=The Madonna Companion: Two Decades of Commentary\n|publisher=[[Music Sales Group]]\n|year=1999\n|isbn=0-8256-7194-9\n|ref=harv\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n|last=Guilbert\n|first=Georges-Claude\n|title=Madonna as postmodern myth\n|publisher=McFarland\n|year=2002\n|isbn=0-7864-1408-1\n|ref=harv\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n|last = Bronson\n|first = Fred\n|title=The Billboard Book of Number 1 Hits\n|publisher=Billboard books\n|year=2003\n|isbn=0-8230-7677-6\n|authorlink=Fred Bronson\n|ref = harv\n}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Discogs master|34721|Music|album}}\n*[https://archive.is/20140324074753/http://catalog.rockhall.com/catalog/45059649 Library + Archives: Music] at the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]\n\n{{Madonna}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2000 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Madonna (entertainer)]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by William Orbit]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Guy Sigsworth]]\n[[Category:Madonna (entertainer) albums]]\n[[Category:Maverick Records albums]]\n[[Category:Electronica albums by American artists]]\n", "name_user": "187.18.129.5", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Music_(Madonna_album)"}
{"title_page": "Alfie Byrne", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Alfie Byrne\n|office        = [[Lord Mayor of Dublin]]\n|image         = Alfred Byrne.jpeg\n|caption       = Byrne in his mayoral robes\n|party         = [[Independent politician|Independent]]\n|birth_name    = Alfred Byrne\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1882|3|17|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Dublin]], Ireland\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1956|3|13|1882|3|17|df=y}}\n|death_place   = Dublin, Ireland\n|nationality   = [[Irish nationality|Irish]]\n|otherparty    = [[Irish Parliamentary Party]]\n|spouse        =\n|children      = [[Patrick Byrne (Irish politician)|Patrick Byrne]]<br/>[[A. P. Byrne]]<br/>[[Thomas Byrne (Dublin politician)|Thomas Byrne]]<br/>Carmel Byrne<ref>{{cite news|title=Bolger, Carmel: Death notice|url=http://notices.irishtimes.com/death/bolger-carmel/35056141|work=Irish Times|date=2 January 2014}}</ref><br/>Frances Elizabeth Byrne<ref>{{cite news|title=Perrott: Death notice|url=http://notices.irishtimes.com/death/perrott/2370912|accessdate=14 October 2017|work=Irish Times|date=15 August 2005}}</ref><br/>Mary Byrne<br/>Sylvester Louis Byrne<ref>{{cite web|title=New arrival at the Mansion House!|url=http://www.dublincity.ie/main-menu-services-press-and-news-read-press-release-press-releases-2013-press-releases-february/new|website=Dublin City Council|accessdate=21 October 2017|date=February 2013}}</ref><br/>Jimmy Byrne\n|imagesize     =\n|term_start    = June 1954\n|term_end      = May 1955\n|term_start2   = June 1930\n|term_end2     = June 1939\n|office3       = [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]\n|term_start3   = July 1937\n|term_end3     = March 1956\n|constituency3 = [[Dublin North-East (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin North-East]]\n|term_start4   = February 1932\n|term_end4     = July 1937\n|term_start5   = August 1923\n|term_end5     = December 1928\n|constituency5 = [[Dublin North (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin North]]\n|term_start6   = June 1922\n|term_end6     = August 1923\n|constituency6 = [[Dublin Mid (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin Mid]]\n|office7       = [[Seanad \u00c9ireann|Senator]]\n|term_start7   = December 1928\n|term_end7     = December 1931\n|office8       = Member of Parliament<br/>for [[Dublin Harbour (UK Parliament constituency)|Dublin Harbour]]\n|term_start8   = October 1915\n|term_end8     = December 1918\n}}\n'''Alfred Byrne''' (17 March 1882 \u2013 13 March 1956) was an Irish politician who [[Records of members of the Oireachtas#Members of both the British Parliament and of the Oireachtas|served as]] a [[Member of Parliament]] (MP), as a [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] (TD) and as [[Lord Mayor]] of [[Dublin]]. He was known as the \"Shaking Hand of Dublin\".<ref name=Shaking/>\n\n==Early life==\nThe second of seven children, he was the son of Thomas Byrne, an engineer, and Fanny Dowman.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://civilrecords.irishgenealogy.ie/churchrecords/details-civil/afaa721775145|title=General Registrar's Office|last=|first=|date=|website=IrishGenealogy.ie|publisher=|access-date=17 March 2017}}</ref> His childhood home was at 36 Seville Place, a terraced house with five rooms just off the [[North Strand]] in Dublin.<ref name=\"soundcloud.com\">{{cite web|author=Niall Curran|title=Alfie Byrne: Dublin's Longest-Serving Lord Mayor and Champion of the Poor|publisher=Dublin City FM|work=Soundcloud|date=2015|url=https://soundcloud.com/20th-century-dubliners/alfie-byrne-dublins-longest-serving-lord-mayor-and-champion-of-the-poor}}</ref> Byrne dropped out of school at the age of 13, and was soon juggling jobs as a grocer's assistant and a bicycle mechanic.<ref name=\"Death of Alderman\">{{cite news|title=Death of Alderman Alfred Byrne: 'Much-Loved Friend of the Poor'|work=[[The Irish Times]] archive|date=14 March 1956|accessdate=28 July 2015|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1956/0314/Pg006.html#Ar00600:1AF0902740EC1691241BA1430BF2070EC21F0A22F20B53090B72F20CE3090E561711162C060B56092B6E160B9B16BBB216CB9B18EBB20DE24E0E52660E624E10C2660702F20943090B86160DD62B1647CA18B7E2168B4318EB5D12EB9B155BB3}}</ref> Eventually he used his savings to buy a pub on [[Talbot Street]].<ref name=\"Death of Alderman\"/> He married Elizabeth Heagney in 1910.<ref>{{cite web|title=General Registrar's Office|url=https://civilrecords.irishgenealogy.ie/churchrecords/details-civil/61da607131547|website=Irishgenealogy.ie|accessdate=19 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\n[[File:Alfred Byrne Purchasing Newspaper.jpeg|thumb|left|Alfie Byrne buying a newspaper]]\nByrne became an [[Alderman]] on Dublin Corporation in 1914. He was a member of the Dublin Port and Docks Board, a significant position for a politician from the Dublin Harbour constituency. In the records of the [[Oireachtas]] his occupation is given as company director. He was elected as [[Member of parliament|MP]] for [[Dublin Harbour (UK Parliament constituency)|Dublin Harbour]] in a [[1915 Dublin Harbour by-election|by-election on 1 October 1915]], as a candidate of the [[Irish Parliamentary Party]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/wit/1915/1009/Pg007.html#Ar00705|title=Alderman Byrne Returned|work=The Irish Times archive|date=9 October 1915|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> and later to [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] as an Independent in favour of the [[Anglo-Irish Treaty]].<ref name=\"Death of Alderman\"/> Without the benefit of a party machine, he soon realised that attending to constituents' needs was the only sure way to retain his seat. In several elections he secured more votes than any other politician in the country.<ref name=\"Anne Dolan 2009\">Anne Dolan, \"Alfred 'Alfie' Byrne\". Dictionary of Irish Biography, ed. by Aidan Clarke, Ronan Fanning, K. Theodore Hoppen, Edith Mary Johnston-Liik, James McGuire, Maureen Murphy, and James Quinn, (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2009), 202</ref> His personal archive, which is on view in [[The Little Museum of Dublin]], includes many letters from men who thought that he could find them a wife.\n\nThe [[Easter Rising]] in 1916 was followed by the rapid decline of the Irish Parliamentary Party and the rise of [[Sinn F\u00e9in]], even in the formerly immensely safe Dublin Harbour constituency. At the [[1918 Irish general election|general election in 1918]] Byrne was defeated by a Sinn F\u00e9in candidate, [[Philip Shanahan]]. Following the establishment of the [[Irish Free State]] Byrne was elected as an [[Independent politician|Independent]] TD for the [[Dublin Mid (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin Mid]] constituency at the [[1922 Irish general election|general election]] to the [[Third D\u00e1il]] in 1922.<ref name=oireachtas_db>{{cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/members/member/Alfred-Byrne.D.1922-09-09/|title=Alfred Byrne|work=Oireachtas Members Database|accessdate=11 April 2012}}</ref> From 1923 to 1928 he represented [[Dublin North (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin North]]. He was an elected member of [[Seanad \u00c9ireann (Irish Free State)|Seanad \u00c9ireann]], for a six-year term from  1928. He vacated his D\u00e1il seat on 4 December 1928. He resigned from the Seanad on 10 December 1931, and returned to the D\u00e1il in 1932. He remained a TD until his death in 1956, representing [[Dublin North (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin North]] (1932\u201337) and [[Dublin North-East (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin North-East]] (1937\u201356).<ref name=elecs_irl>{{cite web|url=http://electionsireland.org/candidate.cfm?ID=1246|title=Alfred Byrne|work=ElectionsIreland.org|accessdate=11 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Lord Mayor (1930\u201339)==\n[[File:Alfred Byrne on O'Connell Bridge.jpeg|thumb|left|Byrne on O'Connell Bridge]]\nByrne was elected as [[Lord Mayor]] of Dublin in 1930,<ref>{{cite news|title=Greater Dublin: The Three New Councils|work=Weekly Irish Times|date=11 October 1930|accessdate=28 July 2015|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/wit/1930/1011/Pg013.html#Ar01301:1188C31438DC1AE8ED1F5905}}</ref> serving in the post for nine consecutive years.<ref>{{cite web|title=He Was Lord Mayor of Dublin Ten Times and Friend to All|work=Irish Pictorial|date=24 March 1956|accessdate=28 July 2015|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/pic/1956/0324/Pg015.html#Ar01511:4F538552039C52038553139C53138556739C0000FE61E1186AD1136BB12D6BB1126DC12E52F13E55A1564F224851A25F5AD2795D729059D3275C233E67D1136A712D50113E5251565DD23860024F55639557C3AC}}</ref> When cycling or walking around the city he dispensed lollipops to children, who were often seen chasing him down the street. With a handshake and a few words for all, his eternal canvassing soon earned him the first of his nicknames: the Shaking Hand of Dublin.<ref name=\"soundcloud.com\"/> Married with eight children, Byrne treated the people of Dublin as his second family.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1956/0319/Pg007.html#Ar00710:41B48244B49C44B48245D49C45D48249849C00037C4F43B04F337D5063B150838053F3AF4D64185044324884944AC4AE|title=Tribute Paid to Alderman Byrne at Service|work=The Irish Times archive|date=19 March 1956|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> Every morning he would find up to fifty people waiting for him in the [[Mansion House, Dublin|Mansion House]]. None had appointments. All were met. Byrne answered 15,000 letters in his first year as Lord Mayor.<ref name=\"The People 1931\">\"Busiest Man in Ireland\". ''The People.'' 1 February 1931.</ref> Many were from Dubliners looking for a job, a house, some advice or a reference. One morning in 1931 a journalist watched the Lord Mayor attend to his correspondence. Within an hour he accepted \"seventeen invitations to public dinners, one invitation to a public entertainment and eight invitations to public functions.\" Then he dictated forty-three sympathetic letters to men and women looking for employment.<ref name=\"The People 1931\" /> In 1937, children between the ages of eight and eleven years old were being sentenced to spend up to five years in Industrial Schools. Their crime was stealing a few apples from an orchard. When Byrne said such sentences were \"savage,\" a judge responded with a defence of the Industrial School system, urging an end to \"ridiculous Mansion House mummery.\"<ref>\"Justices Will Probe Lord Mayor's 'Savage Sentences' Allegations\". ''Daily Express.'' 23 October 1937.</ref> Byrne stood firm: \"For the punishment of trifling offences the home of the children is better than any institution.\"<ref>\"Lord Mayor's Reply to Criticism of Speech: Courts and Children\". ''The Irish Press''. 7 April 1937.</ref> In 1938, Byrne was favoured by the press for the presidency of Ireland, a ceremonial role created in the new Constitution, but he was outgunned by the political establishment.<ref>\"\u00a315,000 a year\". ''Evening Standard'' (London). 8 April 1938.</ref>\n\n==Relations with the United States and the United Kingdom==\n[[File:The Lord Mayor Leaves New York.jpeg|thumb|right|The Lord Mayor Leaves New York]]\nWhen, in 1935, Byrne became the first Lord Mayor of Dublin to visit [[North America]] in 40 years, he was granted the freedom of [[Toronto]], and ''[[The New York Times]]'' hailed the arrival of a \"champion showman.\" <ref name=\"soundcloud.com\"/> Byrne often extended a hand of friendship to [[United Kingdom|Britain]]. He also improved relations between Dublin (until recently the centre of British authority) and the rest of the country. One night [[Dublin Fire Brigade]] got an urgent call for assistance from [[Clones, County Monaghan|Clones]].<ref>\"Lord Mayor of Dublin Cheered at Clones\". ''The Weekly Irish Times.'' 23 October 1937.</ref> As Lord Mayor, Byrne felt obliged to join the men on top of the fire engine as they set off on the 85-mile journey in the middle of the night.<ref>{{cite web|author=Matt Cooper|title=The Last Word with Matt Cooper|work=Today FM|url=http://www.todayfm.com/player/listen_back/7/20940/09th_June_2015_-_The_Last_Word_with_Matt_Cooper_Part_1}}</ref>\n\n==Anti-communist connections==\nIn August 1936, Byrne addressed the inaugural meeting of the [[Anti-communism|anti-communist]] [[Irish Christian Front]], some of whose members later expressed anti-Semitic views.<ref>{{cite web|author=Donal Fallon|url=http://comeheretome.com/2014/12/17/alls-loud-on-the-christian-front|title=All's Loud On The Christian Front|work=Come here to me!}}</ref> In 1938, as lord mayor, he presented a gift of a replica of the [[Ardagh Hoard|Ardagh Chalice]] to Italian naval cadets visiting Dublin on board two warships, who had been welcomed by the Irish government despite the protests of Dubliners.<ref>{{cite web|author=Donal Fallon|url=http://comeheretome.com/2012/09/20/fascist-warships-in-dublin-bay-july-1938|title=Fascist Warships in Dublin Bay|date=July 1938|work=Come here to me!}}</ref> A photograph exists of Byrne giving a fascist salute along with [[Eoin O'Duffy]], commander of the [[Blueshirts]], around 1933.<ref>[http://www.gettyimages.ie/detail/news-photo/irish-fascist-leader-eoin-oduffy-at-a-rally-of-his-news-photo/3239218 Irish fascist leader Eoin O'Duffy at a rally of his Blueshirts. To his right is Alfred Byrne, the Lord Mayor of Dublin], Getty Images.</ref>\n\n==Final term as Lord Mayor (1954)==\nIn 1954, Byrne was elected as Lord Mayor for a record tenth time. This time he did not live in the Mansion House, but stayed in [[Rathmines]] with his family, taking the bus to work each morning.<ref name=\"David McEllin 1950\">David McEllin. \"Legendary Lord Mayor Alfie Byrne\". In Leaders of the City: Dublin\u2019s First Citizen, 1500\u20131950, ed. by Ruth McManus & Lisa-Marie Griffith, (Dublin: Four Courts Press, 2013), 163.</ref> He was just as devoted to the job. When flooding damaged 20,000 houses in Fairview and North Strand, he rose from his sick bed to organize a relief fund.<ref name=\"David McEllin 1950\"/> Byrne's final term as Lord Mayor came to an end in 1955. Shortly afterwards, [[Trinity College, Dublin]] awarded him an honorary Doctorate of Law, describing him as a \"champion of the poor and needy, and a friend of all men.\"<ref>\"Honorary degree for Ald. Byrne\". ''Dublin Evening Mail''. 5 July 1955.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nAlfie Byrne died on 13 March 1956. An obituary in ''[[The Irish Times]]'' noted:<ref name=\"Death of Alderman\"/>\n\n{{quote|For more than forty years, he was a prominent figure in public life, serving his country and city with a rare and single-minded devotion. Himself a true Dubliner, he had a profound understanding of, and deep sympathy for, the needs and interests of his fellow-citizens, especially the poor. It is not too much to say that he lived for them, for wherever there was distress, he was promptly on the spot to ensure that assistance was made available with the utmost speed.}} \n \nByrne's funeral was the largest seen in Dublin for many years. ''[[The Evening Herald]]'' reported that \"Traffic in O'Connell Street was held up for almost 20 minutes to allow the cortege of over 150 motor cars to pass, and at all the junctions along the route to [[Glasnevin]] people silently gathered to pay tribute to one of Dublin\u2019s most famous sons\".<ref>\"Alfie Byrne Obituary\". ''The Evening Herald''. 15 March 1956. Retrieved 29 July 2015.</ref> ''The Irish Times'' noted that \"one of the largest groups of people gathered at the Five Lamps, one of the few places at which Alderman Byrne always made a speech during his election campaign for Dublin North-East.\"<ref name=\"Death of Alderman\" /> ''[[The Irish Press]]'' reported a tribute by the Taoiseach, [[John A Costello]], \"He had great personal charm and was known for his old-world courtliness both at home and abroad.... We mourn in the passing of Alfie Byrne the loss of an honoured and distinguished Irishman whose place in the hearts of his fellow countrymen was unique and who gave a lifetime of unselfish devotion to their service.\"<ref name=\"Death of Alderman\" /> The members of the D\u00e1il stood and observed a short silence as a mark of respect. A telegram was sent to his widow from the Mayor of New York, [[Robert F. Wagner Jr.]], expressing deepest sympathy, and stating \"that Ald. Byrne had attained high office of Lord Mayor many times, but he never lost contact with the poor and the underprivileged, whose champion he was\".<ref>\"Alfie Byrne Obituary\". ''The Irish Press.'' 15 March 1956. Retrieved 28 July 2015.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe press called him the \"Shaking Hand of Dublin\",<ref name=Shaking>{{cite web|author=Frank McNally|title=The Darling of Dublin - An Irishman\u2019s Diary about Alfie Byrne|work=The Irish Times|date=6 June 2015|accessdate=29 July 2015|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/the-darling-of-dublin-an-irishman-s-diary-about-alfie-byrne-1.2239064}}</ref> Alfred the Great,<ref>\"Alfred the Great\" Dublin Opinion 9, no 105 (November 1930).</ref> and The Lord Mayor of Ireland, but most people knew him simply as Alfie.<ref>\"Lord Mayor\u2019s Postbag: 15,000 Letters\". ''The Irish Times''. 13 February 1931.</ref> As one of the most popular Dublin-born politicians of the 20th Century, he did not write a memoir.<ref name=\"Anne Dolan 2009\" /> The [[1956 Dublin North-East by-election|by-election]] caused by his death, was won by his son [[Patrick Byrne (Irish politician)|Patrick Byrne]]. Two other sons [[A. P. Byrne]] and [[Thomas Byrne (Dublin politician)|Thomas Byrne]] were also TDs for various Dublin constituencies. Alfie Byrne Road in [[Clontarf, Dublin|Clontarf]] is named after him. In 2015 a quantity of personal and professional correspondence and documentation, the Alfie Byrne Collection, went on display in [[The Little Museum of Dublin]]. The Dublin Bay North branch of [[Young Fine Gael]] was renamed 'Alfie Byrne YFG'.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Families in the Oireachtas]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*''Who's Who of British Members of Parliament: Vol. II 1886-1918'', edited by M. Stenton & S. Lees (The Harvester Press 1978)\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Alfie Byrne}}\n*{{YouTube | id=Cb--Cy19Lig | title= Interview With Mr Alfred Byrne Lord Mayor Of Dublin (1936), ''British Path\u00e9''}}\n*{{Hansard-contribs|mr-alfred-byrne|Alfred Byrne}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-civ}}\n{{s-bef|before = Position suspended}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Lord Mayor of Dublin]] \n       |years  = 1930\u20131939}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Kathleen Clarke]]}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Bernard Butler (politician)|Bernard Butler]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Lord Mayor of Dublin]] \n       |years  = 1954\u20131955}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Denis Larkin]]}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[William Abraham (Irish politician)|William Abraham]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Irish Parliamentary Party]] [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Dublin Harbour (UK Parliament constituency)|Dublin Harbour]]\n       |years  = [[1915 Dublin Harbour by-election|1915]]\u20131918}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Philip Shanahan]]}}\n{{s-par|ie/oi}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Philip Shanahan]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Independent politician|Independent]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] for [[Dublin Mid (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin Mid]]\n       |years  = 1922\u20131923}}\n{{s-non | reason  = Constituency abolished}}\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Independent politician|Independent]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] for [[Dublin North (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin North]]\n       |years  = 1923\u20131928}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Thomas F. O'Higgins]]}}\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Independent politician|Independent]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] for [[Dublin North (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin North]]\n       |years  = 1932\u20131937}}\n{{s-non|reason  = Constituency abolished}}\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Independent politician|Independent]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] for [[Dublin North-East (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin North-East]]\n       |years  = 1937\u20131956}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Patrick Byrne (Irish politician)|Patrick Byrne]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Members of the 1928 Seanad}}\n{{Members of the 1931 Seanad}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Byrne, Alfie}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1956 deaths]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:Irish Parliamentary Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Dublin constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Independent TDs]]\n[[Category:Local councillors in Dublin (city)]]\n[[Category:Lord Mayors of Dublin]]\n[[Category:Members of the 3rd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 4th D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 5th D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 6th D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 1928 Seanad]]\n[[Category:Members of the 1931 Seanad]]\n[[Category:Members of the 7th D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 8th D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 9th D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 10th D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 11th D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 12th D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 13th D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 14th D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 15th D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Politicians from County Dublin]]\n[[Category:Burials at Glasnevin Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Independent members of Seanad \u00c9ireann]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Alfie Byrne\n|office        = [[Lord Mayor of Dublin]]\n|image         = Alfred Byrne.jpeg\n|caption       = Byrne in his mayoral robes\n|party         = [[Independent politician|Independent]]\n|birth_name    = Alfred Byrne\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1882|3|17|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Dublin]], Ireland\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1956|3|13|1882|3|17|df=y}}\n|death_place   = Dublin, Ireland\n|nationality   = [[Irish nationality|Irish]]\n|otherparty    = [[Irish Parliamentary Party]]\n|spouse        =\n|children      = [[Patrick Byrne (Irish politician)|Patrick Byrne]]<br/>[[A. P. Byrne]]<br/>[[Thomas Byrne (Dublin politician)|Thomas Byrne]]<br/>Carmel Byrne<ref>{{cite news|title=Bolger, Carmel: Death notice|url=http://notices.irishtimes.com/death/bolger-carmel/35056141|work=Irish Times|date=2 January 2014}}</ref><br/>Frances Elizabeth Byrne<ref>{{cite news|title=Perrott: Death notice|url=http://notices.irishtimes.com/death/perrott/2370912|accessdate=14 October 2017|work=Irish Times|date=15 August 2005}}</ref><br/>Mary Byrne<br/>Sylvester Louis Byrne<ref>{{cite web|title=New arrival at the Mansion House!|url=http://www.dublincity.ie/main-menu-services-press-and-news-read-press-release-press-releases-2013-press-releases-february/new|website=Dublin City Council|accessdate=21 October 2017|date=February 2013}}</ref><br/>Jimmy Byrne\n|imagesize     =\n|term_start    = June 1954\n|term_end      = May 1955\n|term_start2   = June 1930\n|term_end2     = June 1939\n|office3       = [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]\n|term_start3   = July 1937\n|term_end3     = March 1956\n|constituency3 = [[Dublin North-East (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin North-East]]\n|term_start4   = February 1932\n|term_end4     = July 1937\n|term_start5   = August 1923\n|term_end5     = December 1928\n|constituency5 = [[Dublin North (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin North]]\n|term_start6   = June 1922\n|term_end6     = August 1923\n|constituency6 = [[Dublin Mid (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin Mid]]\n|office7       = [[Seanad \u00c9ireann|Senator]]\n|term_start7   = December 1928\n|term_end7     = December 1931\n|office8       = Member of Parliament<br/>for [[Dublin Harbour (UK Parliament constituency)|Dublin Harbour]]\n|term_start8   = October 1915\n|term_end8     = December 1918\n}}\n'''Alfred Byrne''' (17 March 1882 \u2013 13 March 1956) was an Irish politician who [[Records of members of the Oireachtas#Members of both the British Parliament and of the Oireachtas|served as]] a [[Member of Parliament]] (MP), as a [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] (TD) and as [[Lord Mayor]] of [[Dublin]]. He was known as the \"Shaking Hand of Dublin\".<ref name=Shaking/>\n\n==Early life==\nThe second of seven children, he was the son of Thomas Byrne, an engineer, and Fanny Dowman.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://civilrecords.irishgenealogy.ie/churchrecords/details-civil/afaa721775145|title=General Registrar's Office|last=|first=|date=|website=IrishGenealogy.ie|publisher=|access-date=17 March 2017}}</ref> His childhood home was at 36 Seville Place, a terraced house with five rooms just off the [[North Strand]] in Dublin.<ref name=\"soundcloud.com\">{{cite web|author=Niall Curran|title=Alfie Byrne: Dublin's Longest-Serving Lord Mayor and Champion of the Poor|publisher=Dublin City FM|work=Soundcloud|date=2015|url=https://soundcloud.com/20th-century-dubliners/alfie-byrne-dublins-longest-serving-lord-mayor-and-champion-of-the-poor}}</ref> Byrne dropped out of school at the age of 13, and was soon juggling jobs as a grocer\u2019s assistant and a bicycle mechanic.<ref name=\"Death of Alderman\">{{cite news|title=Death of Alderman Alfred Byrne: 'Much-Loved Friend of the Poor'|work=[[The Irish Times]] archive|date=14 March 1956|accessdate=28 July 2015|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1956/0314/Pg006.html#Ar00600:1AF0902740EC1691241BA1430BF2070EC21F0A22F20B53090B72F20CE3090E561711162C060B56092B6E160B9B16BBB216CB9B18EBB20DE24E0E52660E624E10C2660702F20943090B86160DD62B1647CA18B7E2168B4318EB5D12EB9B155BB3}}</ref> Eventually he used his savings to buy a pub on [[Talbot Street]].<ref name=\"Death of Alderman\"/> He married Elizabeth Heagney in 1910.<ref>{{cite web|title=General Registrar's Office|url=https://civilrecords.irishgenealogy.ie/churchrecords/details-civil/61da607131547|website=Irishgenealogy.ie|accessdate=19 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\n[[File:Alfred Byrne Purchasing Newspaper.jpeg|thumb|left|Alfie Byrne buying a newspaper]]\nByrne became an [[Alderman]] on Dublin Corporation in 1914. He was a member of the Dublin Port and Docks Board, a significant position for a politician from the Dublin Harbour constituency. In the records of the [[Oireachtas]] his occupation is given as company director. He was elected as [[Member of parliament|MP]] for [[Dublin Harbour (UK Parliament constituency)|Dublin Harbour]] in a [[1915 Dublin Harbour by-election|by-election on 1 October 1915]], as a candidate of the [[Irish Parliamentary Party]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/wit/1915/1009/Pg007.html#Ar00705|title=Alderman Byrne Returned|work=The Irish Times archive|date=9 October 1915|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> and later to [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] as an Independent in favour of the [[Anglo-Irish Treaty]].<ref name=\"Death of Alderman\"/> Without the benefit of a party machine, he soon realised that attending to constituents' needs was the only sure way to retain his seat. In several elections he secured more votes than any other politician in the country.<ref name=\"Anne Dolan 2009\">Anne Dolan, \"Alfred 'Alfie' Byrne\". Dictionary of Irish Biography, ed. by Aidan Clarke, Ronan Fanning, K. Theodore Hoppen, Edith Mary Johnston-Liik, James McGuire, Maureen Murphy, and James Quinn, (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2009), 202</ref> His personal archive, which is on view in [[The Little Museum of Dublin]], includes many letters from men who thought that he could find them a wife.\n\nThe [[Easter Rising]] in 1916 was followed by the rapid decline of the Irish Parliamentary Party and the rise of [[Sinn F\u00e9in]], even in the formerly immensely safe Dublin Harbour constituency. At the [[1918 Irish general election|general election in 1918]] Byrne was defeated by a Sinn F\u00e9in candidate, [[Philip Shanahan]]. Following the establishment of the [[Irish Free State]] Byrne was elected as an [[Independent politician|Independent]] TD for the [[Dublin Mid (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin Mid]] constituency at the [[1922 Irish general election|general election]] to the [[Third D\u00e1il]] in 1922.<ref name=oireachtas_db>{{cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/members/member/Alfred-Byrne.D.1922-09-09/|title=Alfred Byrne|work=Oireachtas Members Database|accessdate=11 April 2012}}</ref> From 1923 to 1928 he represented [[Dublin North (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin North]]. He was an elected member of [[Seanad \u00c9ireann (Irish Free State)|Seanad \u00c9ireann]], for a six-year term from  1928. He vacated his D\u00e1il seat on 4 December 1928. He resigned from the Seanad on 10 December 1931, and returned to the D\u00e1il in 1932. He remained a TD until his death in 1956, representing [[Dublin North (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin North]] (1932\u201337) and [[Dublin North-East (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin North-East]] (1937\u201356).<ref name=elecs_irl>{{cite web|url=http://electionsireland.org/candidate.cfm?ID=1246|title=Alfred Byrne|work=ElectionsIreland.org|accessdate=11 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Lord Mayor (1930\u201339)==\n[[File:Alfred Byrne on O'Connell Bridge.jpeg|thumb|left|Byrne on O'Connell Bridge]]\nByrne was elected as [[Lord Mayor]] of Dublin in 1930,<ref>{{cite news|title=Greater Dublin: The Three New Councils|work=Weekly Irish Times|date=11 October 1930|accessdate=28 July 2015|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/wit/1930/1011/Pg013.html#Ar01301:1188C31438DC1AE8ED1F5905}}</ref> serving in the post for nine consecutive years.<ref>{{cite web|title=He Was Lord Mayor of Dublin Ten Times and Friend to All|work=Irish Pictorial|date=24 March 1956|accessdate=28 July 2015|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/pic/1956/0324/Pg015.html#Ar01511:4F538552039C52038553139C53138556739C0000FE61E1186AD1136BB12D6BB1126DC12E52F13E55A1564F224851A25F5AD2795D729059D3275C233E67D1136A712D50113E5251565DD23860024F55639557C3AC}}</ref> When cycling or walking around the city he dispensed lollipops to children, who were often seen chasing him down the street. With a handshake and a few words for all, his eternal canvassing soon earned him the first of his nicknames: the Shaking Hand of Dublin.<ref name=\"soundcloud.com\"/> Married with eight children, Byrne treated the people of Dublin as his second family.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1956/0319/Pg007.html#Ar00710:41B48244B49C44B48245D49C45D48249849C00037C4F43B04F337D5063B150838053F3AF4D64185044324884944AC4AE|title=Tribute Paid to Alderman Byrne at Service|work=The Irish Times archive|date=19 March 1956|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> Every morning he would find up to fifty people waiting for him in the [[Mansion House, Dublin|Mansion House]]. None had appointments. All were met. Byrne answered 15,000 letters in his first year as Lord Mayor.<ref name=\"The People 1931\">\"Busiest Man in Ireland\". ''The People.'' 1 February 1931.</ref> Many were from Dubliners looking for a job, a house, some advice or a reference. One morning in 1931 a journalist watched the Lord Mayor attend to his correspondence. Within an hour he accepted \"seventeen invitations to public dinners, one invitation to a public entertainment and eight invitations to public functions.\" Then he dictated forty-three sympathetic letters to men and women looking for employment.<ref name=\"The People 1931\" /> In 1937, children between the ages of eight and eleven years old were being sentenced to spend up to five years in Industrial Schools. Their crime was stealing a few apples from an orchard. When Byrne said such sentences were \"savage,\" a judge responded with a defence of the Industrial School system, urging an end to \"ridiculous Mansion House mummery.\"<ref>\"Justices Will Probe Lord Mayor's 'Savage Sentences' Allegations\". ''Daily Express.'' 23 October 1937.</ref> Byrne stood firm: \"For the punishment of trifling offences the home of the children is better than any institution.\"<ref>\"Lord Mayor's Reply to Criticism of Speech: Courts and Children\". ''The Irish Press''. 7 April 1937.</ref> In 1938, Byrne was favoured by the press for the presidency of Ireland, a ceremonial role created in the new Constitution, but he was outgunned by the political establishment.<ref>\"\u00a315,000 a year\". ''Evening Standard'' (London). 8 April 1938.</ref>\n\n==Relations with the United States and the United Kingdom==\n[[File:The Lord Mayor Leaves New York.jpeg|thumb|right|The Lord Mayor Leaves New York]]\nWhen, in 1935, Byrne became the first Lord Mayor of Dublin to visit [[North America]] in 40 years, he was granted the freedom of [[Toronto]], and ''[[The New York Times]]'' hailed the arrival of a \"champion showman.\" <ref name=\"soundcloud.com\"/> Byrne often extended a hand of friendship to [[United Kingdom|Britain]]. He also improved relations between Dublin (until recently the centre of British authority) and the rest of the country. One night [[Dublin Fire Brigade]] got an urgent call for assistance from [[Clones, County Monaghan|Clones]].<ref>\"Lord Mayor of Dublin Cheered at Clones\". ''The Weekly Irish Times.'' 23 October 1937.</ref> As Lord Mayor, Byrne felt obliged to join the men on top of the fire engine as they set off on the 85-mile journey in the middle of the night.<ref>{{cite web|author=Matt Cooper|title=The Last Word with Matt Cooper|work=Today FM|url=http://www.todayfm.com/player/listen_back/7/20940/09th_June_2015_-_The_Last_Word_with_Matt_Cooper_Part_1}}</ref>\n\n==Anti-communist connections==\nIn August 1936, Byrne addressed the inaugural meeting of the [[Anti-communism|anti-communist]] [[Irish Christian Front]], some of whose members later expressed anti-Semitic views.<ref>{{cite web|author=Donal Fallon|url=http://comeheretome.com/2014/12/17/alls-loud-on-the-christian-front|title=All's Loud On The Christian Front|work=Come here to me!}}</ref> In 1938, as lord mayor, he presented a gift of a replica of the [[Ardagh Hoard|Ardagh Chalice]] to Italian naval cadets visiting Dublin on board two warships, who had been welcomed by the Irish government despite the protests of Dubliners.<ref>{{cite web|author=Donal Fallon|url=http://comeheretome.com/2012/09/20/fascist-warships-in-dublin-bay-july-1938|title=Fascist Warships in Dublin Bay|date=July 1938|work=Come here to me!}}</ref> A photograph exists of Byrne giving a fascist salute along with [[Eoin O'Duffy]], commander of the [[Blueshirts]], around 1933.<ref>[http://www.gettyimages.ie/detail/news-photo/irish-fascist-leader-eoin-oduffy-at-a-rally-of-his-news-photo/3239218 Irish fascist leader Eoin O'Duffy at a rally of his Blueshirts. To his right is Alfred Byrne, the Lord Mayor of Dublin], Getty Images.</ref>\n\n==Final term as Lord Mayor (1954)==\nIn 1954, Byrne was elected as Lord Mayor for a record tenth time. This time he did not live in the Mansion House, but stayed in [[Rathmines]] with his family, taking the bus to work each morning.<ref name=\"David McEllin 1950\">David McEllin. \"Legendary Lord Mayor Alfie Byrne\". In Leaders of the City: Dublin\u2019s First Citizen, 1500\u20131950, ed. by Ruth McManus & Lisa-Marie Griffith, (Dublin: Four Courts Press, 2013), 163.</ref> He was just as devoted to the job. When flooding damaged 20,000 houses in Fairview and North Strand, he rose from his sick bed to organize a relief fund.<ref name=\"David McEllin 1950\"/> Byrne's final term as Lord Mayor came to an end in 1955. Shortly afterwards, [[Trinity College, Dublin]] awarded him an honorary Doctorate of Law, describing him as a \"champion of the poor and needy, and a friend of all men.\"<ref>\"Honorary degree for Ald. Byrne\". ''Dublin Evening Mail''. 5 July 1955.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nAlfie Byrne died on 13 March 1956. An obituary in ''[[The Irish Times]]'' noted:<ref name=\"Death of Alderman\"/>\n\n{{quote|For more than forty years, he was a prominent figure in public life, serving his country and city with a rare and single-minded devotion. Himself a true Dubliner, he had a profound understanding of, and deep sympathy for, the needs and interests of his fellow-citizens, especially the poor. It is not too much to say that he lived for them, for wherever there was distress, he was promptly on the spot to ensure that assistance was made available with the utmost speed.}} \n \nByrne\u2019s funeral was the largest seen in Dublin for many years. ''[[The Evening Herald]]'' reported that \"Traffic in O'Connell Street was held up for almost 20 minutes to allow the cortege of over 150 motor cars to pass, and at all the junctions along the route to [[Glasnevin]] people silently gathered to pay tribute to one of Dublin\u2019s most famous sons\".<ref>\"Alfie Byrne Obituary\". ''The Evening Herald''. 15 March 1956. Retrieved 29 July 2015.</ref> ''The Irish Times'' noted that \"one of the largest groups of people gathered at the Five Lamps, one of the few places at which Alderman Byrne always made a speech during his election campaign for Dublin North-East.\"<ref name=\"Death of Alderman\" /> ''[[The Irish Press]]'' reported a tribute by the Taoiseach, [[John A Costello]], \"He had great personal charm and was known for his old-world courtliness both at home and abroad.... We mourn in the passing of Alfie Byrne the loss of an honoured and distinguished Irishman whose place in the hearts of his fellow countrymen was unique and who gave a lifetime of unselfish devotion to their service.\"<ref name=\"Death of Alderman\" /> The members of the D\u00e1il stood and observed a short silence as a mark of respect. A telegram was sent to his widow from the Mayor of New York, [[Robert F. Wagner Jr.]], expressing deepest sympathy, and stating \"that Ald. Byrne had attained high office of Lord Mayor many times, but he never lost contact with the poor and the underprivileged, whose champion he was\".<ref>\"Alfie Byrne Obituary\". ''The Irish Press.'' 15 March 1956. Retrieved 28 July 2015.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe press called him the \"Shaking Hand of Dublin\",<ref name=Shaking>{{cite web|author=Frank McNally|title=The Darling of Dublin - An Irishman\u2019s Diary about Alfie Byrne|work=The Irish Times|date=6 June 2015|accessdate=29 July 2015|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/the-darling-of-dublin-an-irishman-s-diary-about-alfie-byrne-1.2239064}}</ref> Alfred the Great,<ref>\"Alfred the Great\" Dublin Opinion 9, no 105 (November 1930).</ref> and The Lord Mayor of Ireland, but most people knew him simply as Alfie.<ref>\"Lord Mayor\u2019s Postbag: 15,000 Letters\". ''The Irish Times''. 13 February 1931.</ref> As one of the most popular Dublin-born politicians of the 20th Century, he did not write a memoir.<ref name=\"Anne Dolan 2009\" /> The [[1956 Dublin North-East by-election|by-election]] caused by his death, was won by his son [[Patrick Byrne (Irish politician)|Patrick Byrne]]. Two other sons [[A. P. Byrne]] and [[Thomas Byrne (Dublin politician)|Thomas Byrne]] were also TDs for various Dublin constituencies. Alfie Byrne Road in [[Clontarf, Dublin|Clontarf]] is named after him. In 2015 a quantity of personal and professional correspondence and documentation, the Alfie Byrne Collection, went on display in [[The Little Museum of Dublin]]. The Dublin Bay North branch of [[Young Fine Gael]] was renamed 'Alfie Byrne YFG'.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Families in the Oireachtas]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*''Who's Who of British Members of Parliament: Vol. II 1886-1918'', edited by M. Stenton & S. Lees (The Harvester Press 1978)\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Alfie Byrne}}\n*{{YouTube | id=Cb--Cy19Lig | title= Interview With Mr Alfred Byrne Lord Mayor Of Dublin (1936), ''British Path\u00e9''}}\n*{{Hansard-contribs|mr-alfred-byrne|Alfred Byrne}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-civ}}\n{{s-bef|before = Position suspended}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Lord Mayor of Dublin]] \n       |years  = 1930\u20131939}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Kathleen Clarke]]}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Bernard Butler (politician)|Bernard Butler]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Lord Mayor of Dublin]] \n       |years  = 1954\u20131955}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Denis Larkin]]}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[William Abraham (Irish politician)|William Abraham]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Irish Parliamentary Party]] [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Dublin Harbour (UK Parliament constituency)|Dublin Harbour]]\n       |years  = [[1915 Dublin Harbour by-election|1915]]\u20131918}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Philip Shanahan]]}}\n{{s-par|ie/oi}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Philip Shanahan]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Independent politician|Independent]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] for [[Dublin Mid (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin Mid]]\n       |years  = 1922\u20131923}}\n{{s-non | reason  = Constituency abolished}}\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Independent politician|Independent]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] for [[Dublin North (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin North]]\n       |years  = 1923\u20131928}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Thomas F. O'Higgins]]}}\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Independent politician|Independent]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] for [[Dublin North (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin North]]\n       |years  = 1932\u20131937}}\n{{s-non|reason  = Constituency abolished}}\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Independent politician|Independent]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] for [[Dublin North-East (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin North-East]]\n       |years  = 1937\u20131956}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Patrick Byrne (Irish politician)|Patrick Byrne]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Members of the 1928 Seanad}}\n{{Members of the 1931 Seanad}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Byrne, Alfie}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1956 deaths]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:Irish Parliamentary Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Dublin constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Independent TDs]]\n[[Category:Local councillors in Dublin (city)]]\n[[Category